<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pornographic Films Blamed for Violent Crime Increase in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malawi Censorship Board has blamed
the influx of excessively violent and explicitly pornographic
films for the increase of youth involvement in violent crime in
the country, a report reaching here on Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a survey by the board as saying that there
has been a dramatic increase in armed robberies, murder, rape and
defilement by teenagers as a result of an influx of excessively
violent films and pornography.
</P>
<P>
The survey was carried out in Malawi's major urban centers of
Lilongwe, Blantyre, Zomba and Mzuzu.
</P>
<P>
During the six months surveyed, the board found that 109 cases
of sexual abuse against very young children, "some even as young
as two years old", were recorded at police stations and courts,
involving boys of under 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The board noted that there had been a dramatic increase in
commercial sex, involving very young girls, some as young as 10.
</P>
<P>
Violent films, in which those appearing smart and quick with
guns always end up as heroes, make young people adore them so much
that they take after them.
</P>
<P>
"The result is massive increase in school drop-outs due to
early pregnancies and diseases," the board said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
