<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Vows to Create Better Investment Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa has assured foreign investors that his government will
continue with its efforts to create a conducive investment climate
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Talking to visiting Advisory Director Baroness Chalker of the
London-based Unilever Limited Company here on Thursday, Mkapa said
that his government has recognized the importance of foreign
investment to national development.
</P>
<P>
That is why various measures have been taken to improve
institutional and regulatory framework so as to encourage more
foreigners to invest in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will also continue to fight tax evasion
on imports, which has denied Tanzania of a substantial amount of
revenue and paralyzed business development in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government will ensure that existing loopholes in the
trading system that facilitate tax evasion shall be blocked, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has attracted a growing number of investors and
entrepreneurs who are looking at the country with a light of
economic rebirth since the mid-1980's, as embodied in its far-
reaching macro-economic reform programs.
</P>
<P>
Latest official statistics show that foreign investment flow
into Tanzania during the past five years has amounted to 2.5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This could reach 3 billion dollars by this year following heavy
investment flows in the mining industry, an official from the
Tanzania Investment Center said recently.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors that are recording heavy volumes of foreign
investment flows include tourism, manufacturing and natural
resources, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
