<HEADLINE> WB Offers 500 Million U.S. Dollars to Curb HIV/AIDS in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has allocated
500 million U.S. dollars to help facilitate the HIV/AIDS
intervention programs in Ethiopia, said Vice President Calisto
Modva of the World Bank here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia was nominated as one of the priority countries for the
funds of the World Bank because of its firm readiness to contain
the rampant spread of the pandemic in the country, Modva said
while conferring with Ethiopian President Negaso Jidada, who is
also chairman of Ethiopia's National HIV/AIDS Prevention Council.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank official, the establishment of a
nation-wide HIV/AIDS prevention council was a clear testimony of
Ethiopia's unwavering stand to fight the lethal disease.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is working in cooperation with a task force
devised to implement the national HIV/AIDS prevention policy of
the Ethiopian government, Modva said.
</P>
<P>
Negaso applauded the World Bank's decision to assist Ethiopia's
HIV/AIDS prevention endeavors, which he described as timely and
indispensable.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia reportedly has about 350,000 AIDS patients and 2.5
million HIV carriers, ranking the 9th in the African continent.
</P>
</TEXT>
