<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pipeline Fire Rages on in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Firefighters were still working on
Wednesday to put out the oil pipeline fire near Nigeria's
southeast town of Warri, which has left more than 250 people dead.
</P>
<P>
Many more people have suffered serious injuries in the fire
which broke out two days ago at Adeje village, near the town of
Warri in Nigeria's oil-rich Niger delta region.
</P>
<P>
The explosion happened when people were using buckets to
collect petrol flowing from the pipeline after it had been
punctured by thieves on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Warri quoted a local senior police
officer as saying that "an exact toll is unlikely to be clear for
some time but we know more than 250 people have died."
</P>
<P>
Doyin Okupe, President Olusegun Obasanjo's spokesman,
reportedly called on Wednesday the disaster an "avoidable tragedy"
and blamed greedy business operators for encouraging dangerous
pipeline vandalism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
