<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Calls to Reduce Mother-to-Child HIV Transmission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF)
, an international humanitarian body of doctors, Wednesday called
for acceleration of programs to reduce mother-to-child
transmission of HIV.
</P>
<P>
"We are carrying out programs to reduce HIV transmission from
mothers to newborns and we know it is working, but we are seeing a
dramatic impact on people's willingness to get tested and their
attitude toward HIV during the existence of these programs," MSF's
South African head Eric Goemaere said at the 13th International
AIDS Conference in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Many presentations at the Conference have stressed that such
treatment can be effective in poor countries in Africa, Asia and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The question of access to drugs has dominated the meeting of
global AIDS experts, but many delegates also complained that the
political will and funding on national levels have not been
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
"Why should someone get tested (for HIV) if they have no chance
of accessing treatment?" Goemaere said.
</P>
<P>
He said while some African nations like Cote d'Ivoire, Botswana
and Uganda have shown a determination to implement mother-to-child-
transmission programs and begin expanding anti-retroviral pilot
projects, others remain silent.
</P>
<P>
There is also an urgent need for affordable anti-retroviral
drugs in order to begin the implementation of new treatment
strategies, he said, noting that wealthy nations should make firm
commitments to support national programs which UNAIDS estimated
need an additional 3 billion U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
"The spread of AIDS has been exacerbated by the lack of access
to medicines," Goemaere said, stressing that "95 percent of the 34
million people with HIV/AIDS remain without access to treatment.".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
