<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Help Kenya Combat Famine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said here on Wednesday that the U.S. government had promised to
cover one-third of Kenya's needs in combating famine.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks while addressing the Members of Parliament
representing communities whose livelihood depends on livestock at
his Harambee House Office in downtown Nairobi, the Presidential
Press Service (PPS) said.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government has donated 2,500 tons of food including
wheat and rice, valued at approximately 55 million shillings (
about 715,000 U.S. dollars), to Kenya, Moi said, adding that the
greater part of the food has already arrived at the port of
Mombasa while the rest is expected in a few days.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, the Italian government had also
committed to the World Food Program approximately 50 million
shillings (about 650,000 dollars) to cover the cost of transport
and distribution.
</P>
<P>
On June 7, Moi appealed to international donors for emergency
food for 3 million Kenyans in 30 districts hit by prolonged
drought, saying that the country needs 150 million dollars to
tackle the crisis, of which food will take 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
Following the appeal by Moi, some 29,000 tons of relief
supplies comprising wheat, sorghum and yellow maize are expected
to arrive in Mombasa this week, the PPS said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
