<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Poses Greatest Ethical Challenge to Society: Researcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Development of a HIV/AIDS
vaccine and supply of anti-retrovirals to pregnant mothers to
reduce mother-to-child transmission pose as some of the greatest
moral and ethical dilemmas in society, said World Medical Research
Council president William Makgoba on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Makgoba was speaking at the 13th International AIDS Conference
on the ethics of AIDS research in developing countries, where the
spread of the disease has reached alarming proportions with no
possible cure in sight.
</P>
<P>
He said the affordability and sustainabilitty of treatments
within a society that prides itself in human rights and promotes
equity and development has posed great ethical dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps no disease has challenged the ethical and moral
principles of a society such as HIV/AIDS," he said.
</P>
<P>
His comments came amid numerous calls at the conference for
greater accessibility to drugs, which are currently unaffordable
to 95 percent of HIV/AIDS sufferers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, acting South African Constitutional Court judge Edwin
Cameron confirmed that one of the greatest ethical challenges
facing South Africa in particular, is that people, who are
dependent on the public health system, are dying without even the
hope of using medication to prolong their life.
</P>
<P>
Some people are able to afford to "buy life", while millions of
others are dying because they do not have access to drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another moral dilemma for South Africa is the HIV transmission
from mother to babies.
</P>
<P>
Presently, more than 5,000 HIV-positive babies are born in
South Africa every month, and this figure is increasing as there
is no treatment available to infected pregnant mothers who are
looking to the government for help.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision not to provide them with the anti-
retroviral AZT is mainly based on the fact that it is too costly.
</P>
</TEXT>
