Lebanon's position on the Palestinian refugees' fate -- they must
go back to their country.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon's position on the problem of Palestinian refugees,
which is regarded as a timing bomb, is nonnegotiable and
unchangeable because of Lebanon's basic requirements," Lahoud said
in a statement released Friday. (BC-Lebanon-Palestinian Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- U.N. envoy Terje Roed-Larsen arrived in Beirut Friday
with Israel's pledge to terminate the last nine encroachments on
the Lebanese border by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Larsen told reporters after his meeting with Lebanese President
Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss that two expert teams
from Lebanon and the United Nations are scheduled to explore the
border on the ground on Monday so as to "see everything goes
smoothly."
</P>
<P>
The envoy has not specified the exact date of Israel's
operation. (BC-Lebanon-UN) 
</P>
