<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Humanitarian Coordinator, UNICEF Angola Urge Immediate Release of Abducted Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14(Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Humanitarian Coordinator in Angola and UNICEF(United Nations
Children's Fund) Angola on Friday expressed shock and sadness
over last weekend's attack by a group of about 100 armed bandits
on Children's Town in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The unprovoked crime took place in the evening of July 9 in
Quissala, Huambo Province, Angola, which constituted a gross
violation of Angolan children's rights. It also demonstrated once
again that children are often the prime and most vulnerable
casualties in countries in conflict.
</P>
<P>
During the attack, one sixteen year old boy was killed and
four children between 14 to 16 years of age were injured. These
children are now being treated for their injuries. However, 21
other children between 11 to 18 years of age were abducted by the
bandits and their current welfare and whereabouts are unknown.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Humanitarian Coordinator in Angola and UNICEF Angola
called upon the perpetrators of this crime to ensure the safety
and immediate release of the children who are simply innocent
victims of the precarious security situation that continues to
exist in Angola.
</P>
<P>
This is the second such attack against Children's Town.
Earlier this year in a similar attack, 3 children and 1 guard were
killed and 6 children were injured.
</P>
<P>
 The Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Assistance (
OCHA)in Angola and UNICEF also appealed to both national and
provincial authorities to pay special attention to the protection
of Angola children in such child-oriented environments.
</P>
<P>
 The Children's Town is home to 80 children and youth who
participate in various developmental education, sports and
cultural activities.
</P>
<P>
 UNICEF and OCHA strongly condemned all such violent attacks
against children and on nongovernmental organizations which were
working to improve the already difficult lives faced by many of
Angola's children and youth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
