<HEADLINE> Czech Association of Forced Laborers Praises Law on Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Association of Forced
Laborers on Friday praised the German parliament for passing a law
earlier in the day on the compensation of victims of Nazi slave
labor during World War II.
</P>
<P>
"After a year and a half of negotiations with Germany we
finally achieved what we wanted. After 44 years it means not only
financial but also moral compensation," the Czech News Agency
quoted deputy chairman of the association karel Horak as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached between Germany and the Czech
Republic, a total of 423 million marks (203 million U.S. dollars)
will be paid to 67,000 victims in the Czech Republic. Those
payments will fall into two categories. Slave laborers detained in
Nazi concentration camps are eligible for 15,000 marks (7,212 U.S.
dollars) per person, while forced laborers can receive a maximum
payment of 5,000 marks (2,404 U.S. dollars) per person.
</P>
<P>
The fund will come from a German compensation foundation named"
Reminder, Responsibility, Future". Horak said the compensation
could begin before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
During World War II, between 10 million and 14 million people
were forced to work for Nazi Germany, most of whom were persecuted
to death. In late 1999, the German government and business agreed
to pay 10 billion marks (4.81 billion U.S. dollars) as
compensation to those victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
