<HEADLINE> Chavez Keeps Ahead in Venezuelan Electoral Preferences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
preferences rating dropped, but still maintains a wide advantage
over his rivals in the electors preferences for the July 31 voting.
</P>
<P>
Chavez has 48 percent of the voting preferences, compared to
the 50 percent rating he obtained in May, and surpasses his
closest competitor Francisco Arias by 15 points, according to the
poll of the "Mercanalisis" canvassing firm, published Friday by
the press.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan president is not the only one that had a
popularity descent. Also his rivals.
</P>
<P>
Arias went down from 37 to 31 percent in the voters preferences,
having lost six points since May, and Claudio Fermin dropped down
from six to four percent.
</P>
<P>
The undecided voters increased in number from eight to 16
percent, said the poll, made between June 23 and July 2 among 2,
000 persons of the main cities of the country.
</P>
<P>
Mercanalisis attributed the increase in the number of the
undecided to the apathy caused by the cancellation of May 28
elections.
</P>
<P>
Chavez obtained 54 percent of the options, and Arias 35 percent.
Arias, a military man like Chavez, was governor of the oil-rich
Zulia state.
</P>
<P>
The presidency of the republic, the governorships of several
states, mayoralties, deputy chairs in the local congress and
representations in the Andean and Latin American parliaments will
be disputed in the July 30 elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
