<HEADLINE> Annan Looks Forward to New Effort Despite Bleak View of Western Sahara Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- While offering a rather
bleak assessment of the current status of talks on the dispute
over Western Sahara, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Friday
expressed the hope for some progress at the forthcoming meetings
of experts and recommended a three-month extension of the U.N.
mission in Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report on Western Sahara to the Security Council,
Annan said that despite the efforts of his personal Envoy, James
Baker III, there had been no progress during the June 28 meeting
in London in resolving any of the multiple problems impending the
implementation of the 1988 settlement plan.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said the meeting, instead of resolving
the problems, had moved things backwards, with parties, Morocco
and the Popular Front for the Liberation of Saguia el-Hamra and
Rio de Oro, restating their known positions without showing any
willingness to bridge the differences.
</P>
<P>
"They both insisted on a 'winner-take-all approach' and did
not appear willing to discuss a solution where each would get some,
but not all, of what each wanted," Annan said in the report.
</P>
<P>
"Nor did they appear disposed to put aside mutual animosity and
begin to negotiate a political solution that would resolve their
dispute over Western Sahara," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that a political solution was far more preferable
than a breakdown of the process which might lead to a return to
hostilities, the Secretary-General suggested that "the Security
Council reflect on the problem of ensuring that the results of the
referendum, were one to be held, are respected by the parties."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Annan expressed the hope that the upcoming
expert-level meeting in Geneva meetings would yield progress on
the questions regarding appeals, prisoners of war and refugees.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Secretary-General recommended that the
Security Council extend the mandate of the United Nations Mission
for a Referendum in Western Sahara until October 31, 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
