<HEADLINE> Lebanon Stresses Necessity of Palestinian Refugees' Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
Friday reiterated Lebanon's position on the Palestinian refugees'
fate -- they must go back to their country.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon's position on the problem of Palestinian refugees,
which is regarded as a timing bomb, is nonnegotiable and
unchangeable because of Lebanon's basic requirements," Lahoud said
in a statement released Friday.
</P>
<P>
He also said all refugees that were expelled since 1948 should
be allowed to return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
The president had pointed out before Israel's withdrawal from
south Lebanon on May 24 that the existence of Palestinian refugees
in Lebanon is "a security problem."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon refused to give Israel any security guarantees after its
unilateral pullout because thousands of armed Palestinian refugees
in Lebanon "ask for the right to go back."
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are 350,000 Palestinian refugees
living in 12 camps in Lebanon. Most of them were forced out in 1948
when Israel was established. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
