<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,933 Hectares of Forests Devoured by Flame in Turkey Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2,933 hectares of forests
were burnt down to ashes in 58 separate fires throughout Turkey on
Thursday, one of the hottest days in the country in decades, said
the Forestry Ministry on Friday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, all the fire spots, mostly kindled by heat, were
brought under control now, Anatolia News Agency quoted ministry
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
A heat wave has been hitting Turkey for days with its climax so
far appearing on Thursday, when the average temperature reached 40
degrees Celsius, the hottest day in the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
In several western and southwestern woods-intensive provinces
such as Yalova, Bandirma, Kocaeli and Izmir, the temperature
reached 45.4 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that in Buldan town in western Aegean province
of Denizli alone, 1,050 hectares of forests were devoured by flame.
</P>
<P>
Forestry Minister Nami Cagan is expected to visit the town later
on Friday, Anatolia said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said a total of 9,601 hectares of forested area
were burnt down in 722 separate spots throughout the country
between January 1 and July 13 of this year, as compared to 1,021
hectares of forested area burnt down in 659 fires in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has warned people against forest fires during their
tour in summer holidays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
