<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy in Lebanon With Israeli Pledge to End Encroachments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. envoy Terje Roed-Larsen arrived
in Beirut Friday with Israel's pledge to terminate the last nine
encroachments on the Lebanese border by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Larsen told reporters after his meeting with Lebanese President
Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss that two expert teams
from Lebanon and the United Nations are scheduled to explore the
border on the ground on Monday so as to "see everything goes
smoothly."
</P>
<P>
The envoy has not specified the exact date of Israel's
operation.
</P>
<P>
However, Hoss complained of the lengthy time required for the
operation.
</P>
<P>
"The nature of the encroachments shows that they can be
corrected within one hour, or two hours at most," Al Hayat
newspaper quoted him as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from the U.N. headquarters in New York said
Lebanon has formally asked the Security Council for another six-
month routine extension of the mandate of the United Nations
Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) as of July 31.
</P>
<P>
The extension request was delivered on Thursday by Lebanese
Ambassador to the United Nations Selim Tadmori, who told reporters
that he foresees no hitch against a unanimous Security Council
approval of the request.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local media reported that Hezbollah guerrillas have
lately set up 20 observation posts stretching from Naqoura on the
Mediterranean coast to the foothills of Mount Hermon on the
Lebanese-Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
An Nahar newspaper said guerrillas are maintaining permanent
patrols at all key sections of the 110-kilometer frontier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
