<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Orangemen Split over Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Portadown Orangemen in Northern
Ireland Friday rejected a call from the Grand Master of the Orange
Order to end street protests as part of their Drumcree march
campaign.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, Grand Master Robert Saulters said the Order
was in danger of losing public support over the protests around
Northern Ireland - which have often dissolved into violence in the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Saulters said it was now time for the Order to reflect on its
position.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 20 foot high steel barrier which prevented
loyalist protesters on Drumcree hill forcing their way into the
mainly nationalist Garvaghy Road area, has been dismantled.
</P>
<P>
The miles of razor and barbed wire stretched out in the fields
alongside the barrier, were also removed by soldiers early on
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Saulters told BBC that any future protests should be maintained
only on Drumcree hill.
</P>
<P>
Saulters was responding to a further call from Portadown
District Lodge for more street demonstrations in support of their
protest over being barred from marching down the mainly
nationalist Garvaghy Road for the third year running.
</P>
<P>
After a 48-hour break in the violence and disorder for the
traditional July 12, Portadown Orangemen said they were calling
for more "sporadic peaceful protests" on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constabulary said a
strong security force presence would be maintained at Drumcree and
that the measures could be reinstalled at any time if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The past week has seen tourism and industry suffer as many
towns across Northern Ireland were paralyzed by loyalist road
blocks in support of the Drumcree stand-off.
</P>
<P>
And protests degenerated into violence when other elements took
over at night, shooting at and petrol bombing security forces,
hijacking and burning cars and wrecking property.
</P>
<P>
Police and soldiers have begun dismantling the security
fortifications and barbed wire in place at Drumcree and in
Portadown for over a week but an RUC spokesman said a strong
police and military presence would be maintained in the area and
the barriers could be quickly re-erected if necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
