<HEADLINE> Sustained Growth Brings Tax Cuts to C$ 6 Billion: Scotiabank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Sustained economic growth will
bring Canada's tax cuts to more than 6 billion Canadian dollars (
about 4.1 billion U.S. dollars) this year, one of the country's
leading banks forecast.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Nova Scotia said in a report reaching here Friday
that with the expansion of national revenues, the country could
afford a total of 6.1 billion Canadian dollars, of which 3.3
billion (about 2.2 billion U.S. dollars) will be at the federal
level and 2.8 billion(about 1.9 billion U.S. dollars) at the
provincial level.
</P>
<P>
The report came after the federal government said Thursday that
its revenues were up 11.2 percent as of April this year, compared
with a year ago, with its budget surplus reaching 2.7 billion
Canadian dollars (about 1.8 billion U.S. dollars) in April.
</P>
<P>
The bank expects the country's overall growth rate to be at 4.
5 percent this year and to moderate to a more sustainable 3.2
percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Ontario, the most populous and richest province in the country,
is estimated to reach a growth rate of 5.2 percent for this year
and 3.3 percent for next year.
</P>
<P>
Alberta will lead the country in the growth with a rate of 6.2
percent this year and 4 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth in Quebec will be 3.8 percent this year and 3
percent next, while the Atlantic region is predicted to have a
rate of 3 percent for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The bank report illustrates a rosy picture of Canada's economy
in years to come as one with low interest rates, low inflation and
a sustained booming rate to encourage consumer confidence.
</P>
