<HEADLINE> Russia Protests French Seizure of Sailing Vessel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia lodged a strong protest
Friday with France over its seizure of a Russian sailing vessel a
day earlier.
</P>
<P>
Moscow "has demanded that measures be taken immediately for the
release of this vessel," the Russian Foreign Ministry said in a
report on its protest with the French ambassador to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia "views these steps as illegal and causing further
serious damage to Russian- French relations," the Interfax news
agency quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The French side bears all responsibility for the consequences
of these actions."
</P>
<P>
The "Sedov," a training sailboat that arrived in the French
port city of Brest to take part in an international regatta at the
French authorities' invitation, was seized by a local bailiff.
</P>
<P>
The move was believed to be related to a lawsuit brought by the
Swiss company Noga that is pressing for the payment of debts by
the Russian government, Russian media said.
</P>
<P>
The French authorities consider the vessel as part of Russian
state property and therefore liable to seizure under the lawsuit,
Interfax quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry vowed to "continue to persistently
urge the French authorities to take prompt steps to end this
judicial arbitrariness and violation of fundamental principles of
international rights in relation to Russian diplomatic
representations and Russian property in France."
</P>
<P>
"Paris was not deterred by either the exceptionally
humanitarian nature of the vessel's journey or that young students
are aboard."
</P>
<P>
The Russian students were left to celebrate France's national
holiday, July 14, under arrest, the Foreign Ministry noted
ironically, Interfax said. 
</P>
