<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airport Staff Testifies at Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A Maltese airport
supervisor on Friday testified at the Lockerbie trial that an
unaccompanied suitcase could have been placed aboard a flight from
the Mediterranean island state to Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
Wilfred Borg, who was the general manager for ground handling
operations at the Luqa airport in Malta, denied that the records
of unidentified luggage produced by the prosecution indicate a
violation of airport safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
Borg was questioned for hours by the prosecutors about safety
check-ups at the Maltese airport. But he said that an airplane's
captain has to make the final call on safety of his craft.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Alan Turnbull pointed out a number of discrepancies
in Air Malta's luggage loading logs in 1988 and that access to
loading areas could have breached the airport's safety rules.
</P>
<P>
Defendants, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa
Fhimah, who worked for the Libyan Arab Airlines in Malta at that
time, were accused of placing a bomb within an unaccompanied
suitcase which was then transferred in Frankfurt onto the New York-
bound Pan Am Flight 103.
</P>
<P>
The mid-air explosion of the airliner over the Scottish town of
Lockerbie killed all 259 people on board and 11 others on the
ground on December 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Both defendants denied the charges of conspiracy of murder and
breaching of international aircraft safety regulations.
</P>
<P>
The Lockerbie trial went underway on May 3 after almost 12
years of investigation and preparation and is expected to last up
to a year. If convicted, the two Libyans have to serve their life
sentence in Scotland. If the prosecution could not prove its case
beyond reasonable doubt, the two Libyans would then be set free.
</P>
<P>
The Scottish court on Dutch soil had to adjourn for one day
after a group of Maltese witnesses refused to travel to central
Netherlands to testify on airport security. The court resumed on
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
