<HEADLINE> VersaTel Applies for UMTS Auction in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch telecoms network
VersaTel on Friday announced that it had applied to join the
auction of third-generation mobile phone licenses in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Belgium has planned to open its auction of four Universal
Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS) licenses in the coming
September and the licenses will be offered in December.
</P>
<P>
VersaTel is rolling out a fiber optic network of some 2,200
kilometers in the Benelux region that includes Belgium, Luxembourg
and the Netherlands, offering small and medium-sized enterprises
broadband high-speed access to the Internet to facilitate e-
commerce.
</P>
<P>
UMTS offers telecommunications speed 40 times higher than the
that of the existing GSM system.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch firm is at the moment one of the six bidders for five
Dutch UMTS licenses that will allow mobile phone users to download
videos and to access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
It is the only bidder in the Dutch auction without mobile phone
assets.
</P>
<P>
Around 14 European countries are hoping to garner around 100
billion euro (95 billion U.S. dollars) from the auctions of
licenses for the third-generation mobile phone services, also
known as 3G.
</P>
<P>
By Friday, the Dutch auction of 3G mobile phone licenses that
started on July 6 has raised 510 million euro (484.5 million
dollars). Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm expected to raise 20
billion Dutch guilders from the auction or the equivalent of 9.1
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is the second country in Europe after Britain
to have auctioned licenses for the 3G services. The British
government in April netted 22.5 billion pounds (34 billion dollars)
from the auction awards of five UMTS licenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
