<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother May Set Your Body Clock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The reason that jet lag hits
some travelers hard and barely fazes others may lie in our mother'
s genes, the journal Science reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A French study on circadian clocks, which regulate the body's
daily cycles, found that female zebrafish "set" the clocks of
their young before birth.
</P>
<P>
Scientists who conducted the study at the Ecole Normale
Superieure found that a key component of the circadian clock
starts "ticking" in Zebrafish eggs even before they are fertilized.
The gene's activity keeps the same rhythm as the animal develops.
</P>
<P>
"These findings were quite a surprise. The current belief is
that circadian rhythms need a developed brain, so they don't get
started until later," said Vincent Laudet, co-author of the
Science paper.
</P>
<P>
Variations in certain maternal genes may therefore affect how
easily the body's time-keeping system adjusts to changes in the
day/night cycle, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said it was unclear how closely related the study
was to humans.
</P>
<P>
The next step is to find out just how much of the circadian
clock is inherited in assembled form. Laudet and his colleagues
did find another gene, for example, that does not seem to
participate in the circadian cycle until later in development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
