<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks in 4 EU Countries Warned of Cartel Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 109 banks in four
European Union countries were warned on Friday that investigation
would be underway for their cartel practices.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, released a list of these banks which have received
statements of objections in relation to a cartel investigation
into the fixing of charges for exchanging currencies in the euro
zone.
</P>
<P>
Such statements are a step in anti-trust proceedings but do not
pre-judge the final outcome of the investigation, commission
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six banks in Belgium, seven in Finland, nine in Ireland
and 27 in Portugal have been sorted out by the commission for the
investigation. Banks and other recipients of the statements have
until early October to reply to the commission's objections.
</P>
<P>
The statements present documentary evidence to the fact that
the listed banks and banking associations in these four countries
have fixed the prices for the exchange of euro zone currencies.
</P>
<P>
If confirmed by investigation, the practice will constitute an
infringement of the European Union's Amsterdam treaty. The treaty
prohibits cartels and other concerted practices harmful for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
The commission is also investigating other banks in other euro
zone countries and is expected to release the list of those banks
and banking associations as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
