<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Gore Still Haunted by Fund-raising Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, at her weekly press briefing
Thursday, confirmed that she has received a recommendation from
Justice Department prosecutor Robert Conrad to name a special
counsel to investigate whether Gore told truth about the fund-
raising activities.
</P>
<P>
Though Reno is yet to decide whether to name a special counsel,
Conrad's recommendation has posed new problems for Gore, who has
struggled to get his presidential campaign on track before the
November election. Gore has trailed Republican rival George W.
Bush in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation from Conrad, chief of the Justice Department
's campaign finance reform, has not only held ominous implications
for Gore but also put Reno in an awkward situation. Reno has
struggled to bring an end to the fund-raising case, having twice
refused to submit Gore to the scrutiny of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
Last month, in an effort to defuse the controversy, Gore
released a transcript of the April interview with the Federal
Bureau of Investigation (FBI) in which he denied taking part in an
illegal fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple in California.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement officials said Gore's answers appeared to
provide little evidence of wrongdoing to justify referring the
case to an outside independent counsel, a step that they said Reno
would take only if there was evidence that Gore had deliberately
lied to a conceal a relevant fact.
</P>
<P>
Since the expiration of the independent counsel law, Reno has
named only one special counsel. She appointed former Senator John
Danforth, a Missouri Republican, to investigate allegations of
wrongdoing by the FBI during the agency's 1993 tear gas assault on
the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
Gore's release of the 123-page interview transcript has quieted
some of the criticism, but his political rivals will definitely
not let him go without wounding him as the election is drawing
near, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The decision whether to appoint an independent counsel will
risk prolonging an issue that has dogged Gore's presidential
campaign and threaten to bring renewed comparisons to the scandals
of the Clinton administration, the analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
