<HEADLINE> Canadian Military Reveals Peacekeeper Thuggery in Haiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadian military has revealed
cases of thuggery involving some Canadian soldiers sent to Haiti
on peace-keeping mission in 1997.
</P>
<P>
An investigation report made public here Friday said those
soldiers of a United Nations peace-keeping force intimidated and
assaulted local Haitians who infiltrated military camps.
</P>
<P>
In one case, several soldiers in Nine Platoon of the Van Doos
blindfolded, assaulted and threatened Haitian civilians who were
captured while trying to infiltrate their camp.
</P>
<P>
On another occasion, a Haitian intruder was caught and forced
to keel on rocky ground.
</P>
<P>
Two soldiers being charged of assault have testified that they
were under orders from their commanding officer to engage in "
tactical interrogation" and to intimidate infiltrators.
</P>
<P>
The worst case took place in the early 1990s, when a member of
the now disbanded Canadian Air-borne Regiment tortured and beat a
16-year-old child named Shidane Arone, who later died from his
wounds, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The actions led a military police officer to submit a report of
the events directly to National Defense Headquarters in Ottawa. In
response, the Canadian Forces national Investigation Service
deployed an investigation team to Haiti to for the probe of the
Thuggery cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
