<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wholesale Prices Surge 0.6 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. wholesale prices rose 0.6
percent in June, led by the biggest jump in gasoline and other
energy costs in three months and a record increase in residential
natural gas prices, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increase of the department's Producer Price Index, which
measures inflation pressures before they reach consumers, came
after prices were flat in May. The advance in June marked the
biggest increase in wholesale prices since a 0.9 percent rise in
March.
</P>
<P>
In June, all energy prices rose 5.1 percent, the biggest
increase since March, and followed a 0.5 percent drop in May.
Gasoline prices rose 11.8 percent, also the largest increase since
March. Residential natural gas costs increased by a record 5.7
percent last month, surpassing the previous record gain set in
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Rising energy prices eclipsed falling prices for food, which
declined by 0.3 percent, the steepest decrease since October. In
May, food prices fell 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, the "core"
rate of inflation at the wholesale level fell an unexpected 0.1
percent in June, the best showing since January, suggesting that
most other prices were well-behaved. In May, core prices rose 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, wholesale prices have been rising at an
annual rate of 4.8 percent, compared with a 3 percent gain for all
of 1999. The pickup in this year's wholesale prices largely
reflects rising energy costs.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the last year to slow economic growth and keep inflation under
control.
</P>
<P>
In another report, the Commerce Department said that retail
sales rose by a slightly bigger-than-expected 0.5 percent in June,
but excluding the volatile automobiles category sales rose just 0.
2 percent, weaker than expectations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Oks Deepest Tax Cut in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bundesrat (upper house) of
Germany on Friday approved a tax reform bill which will amount to
the deepest reduction in the country's modern history.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, which was proposed by the coalition
government of the Social Democrat Party and the Green party and
already passed through the Bundestag (lower house), was approved
by 41 of 69 votes in the Bundesrat, more than the 35 ballots
necessary.
</P>
<P>
The clear majority emerged in the upper house, which is
composed by representatives from the states, after five coalition-
led states were promised financial help from the federal
government and swung to the approval of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
Claiming a "great day for Germany", Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder said following the voting that the legislation, which is
to enter effect from the beginning of next year, will provide
precondition for continued economic growth and further reduction
in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Hans Eichel estimated that the measures in
the legislation will lead to an overall reduction of 60 billion
Deutsche Marks in company and personal taxes from 2001 to 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
