<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE -- Some white commercial farmers in Zimbabwe have been
given up to a week to leave their farms or face massive disruption
of farming operations by war veterans in the country, The Herald
newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ultimatums come just days before the launch of the
government-sponsored resettlement program. (Zimbabwe-Land Issue)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The U.S. Forces Korea (USFK) Friday admitted that its
headquarters at the Yongsan compound in the central Seoul dumped
toxic chemicals into the Han River.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the USFK confirmed that its Yongsan
compound released 20 gallons (75.7 liters) of formaldehyde last
February. (SKorea-US-Chemical)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev on Friday
blasted the proposed reorganization of the country's strategic
missile force, branding the plan as imbecility and a crime against
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev, accompanying President Vladimir Putin on a visit to
Nizhny Tagil to attend an arms show in central Russia, threatened
to step down if the plan goes ahead. (Russia-Military-
Reorganization)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 135 people died in the past three days in
incessant rains that savaged Maharashtra, Gujarat and Andhra
Pradesh in southwest India, as army began rescue operations in
marooned areas in Ahmedabad Friday which received one of the
heaviest downpours in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
Maharashtra, which bore the brunt of the rain fury, accounted
for 98 deaths, Andhra Pradesh 22 and Gujarat 15, officials in
state capitals said. (India-Rain) 
</P>
