<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Starts 2002 World Cup Qualifier against Guatemala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. men's soccer team will
open its bid for the 2002 World Cup on the road against Guatemala
on Sunday with much pressure as Guatemala put the game in the
heart of its most passionate fan base in the town of Mazatenango.
</P>
<P>
"For Central American countries, these games are big, not only
for their players but also for the whole country," said U.S. head
coach Bruce Arena, "They have great pressure on them so they rise
to the occasion, both on the field and in the stands, and that
makes it more difficult for the visitors."
</P>
<P>
Arena who took the helm of the U.S. national squad after the
1998 World Cup in France, is 5-1-3 this year and 12-5-7 in two
years, warning that the passion of the Guatemalan fans could have
a big impact on the game.
</P>
<P>
"These people live for these games, and it's a cultural
expirence that's second to none," said Arena whose squad will play
six games over the next four months as part of a four-team
semifinal group for teams from the North and Central America and
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
From the region, the top two teams from each of the three
groups will advance to the next year's six-nation final round,
from which three will qualify for the 2002 World Cup. Mexico and
the United States are heavily favored to make it, with the last
bid considered up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
After failing to qualify for the World Cup between 1950 and
1990, the United States has participated in the past three
tournaments, including the 1994 edition as the hosts, and was
aiming for the fourth straight outing despite the last-place
finish in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
