<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Olympic Bid Leaders Spurn Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Two Salt Lake Olympic bid
committee leaders rejected a plea-bargain offer from the U.S.
Justice Department on Thursday, leaving federal prosecutors to
plot their next move in the corruption probe and Olympic officials
to hope there's not a drawn-out trial that coincides with the 2002
Games.
</P>
<P>
Tom Welch and Dave Johnson, who led Salt Lake's successful bid,
turned down the government's offer to plead guilty to charges of
tax evasion, reportedly because they felt the charges were too
sweeping.
</P>
<P>
Federal prosecutors can make a new offer, or they can seek
indictments as the Olympics are 19 months away.
</P>
<P>
The Salt Lake scandal, in which the International Olympic
Committee members voting for the 2002 host city received 1.2
million US dollars in trips, gifts and scholarships, is in its
19th month.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to put pressure on any party, but I hope the
discussions could lead to a resolution that would not involve a
lengthy, painful trial," said Salt Lake Olympic Committee
president Mitt Romnye. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
