<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Thailand Eyes Agriculture As Key for Sustainable Development  By Yuan Li </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Southeast Asian financial
crisis made Thailand realize that a strong agricultural sector
could help guarantee social stability and sustain development, a
senior Thai agriculture ministry official told Xinhua in an
interview recently.
</P>
<P>
"The costly economic crisis taught us that if not for the
strong agricultural sector Thailand would have fallen into a
disaster as some of our neighboring countries had experienced,"
said Ampon Kittiampon, assistant permanent secretary of
agriculture and cooperatives ministry.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is Southeast Asia's most successful agricultural
exporter. Besides being the world's leading rice exporter, it's
also the world's largest exporter of canned pineapple and
processed tuna. The country also ranks in the top 10 in frozen
chicken export.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Thailand's total agricultural exports brought in 6.75
billion U.S. dollars, accounting for almost 20 percent of total
exports value.
</P>
<P>
Sufficient grain supply guaranteed food security for Thailand
during the economic crisis beginning in the summer of 1997, and
thus laid a foundation for social stability, Ampon said.
</P>
<P>
"Just imagine what will happen when a country's currency was
devalued by 100 percent and it needs to import food. What will
happen when people are hungry?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural sector was also proved to be the one that offered
the most abundant opportunities of employment during the crisis
years, he noted.
</P>
<P>
When the crisis occurred and people were laid off from
factories, they went back to their villages and cultivated their
fields. "Once people have enough food, they will not take to the
street to demonstrate," said the 45-year-old senior official.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Thailand's strong agricultural sector also
contributed a lot to the country's faster-than-expected recovery
from the crisis, Ampon said, citing that stable food prices helped
relieve the pressure of inflation and outstanding export
performance of agricultural sector earned precious foreign
exchange for the country in the hard times.
</P>
<P>
Working in the ministry for more than 20 years, the western-
educated technocrat with a doctorate degree in applied economics
loves agriculture and farmers. He refers to agriculture not only
as a sector producing money but also a sector helping preserving
natural resources and social and cultural traditions.
</P>
<P>
"Agriculture is a mark of civilization for the mankind. It is
beyond economy. It is a part of our society, and a part of our
culture," said Ampon.
</P>
<P>
However, during the booming years, resources were directed away
from agriculture to industry and services.
</P>
<P>
"Bearing in mind a booming picture of industrial development
and foreign investment inflow, we jumped into the industrial
sector and neglected the real need of the majority of our people --
farmers," Ampon said.
</P>
<P>
Though agriculture accounts for only 12 percent of Thailand's
gross domestic products, about 60 percent of Thais depend on
agriculture for at least part of their income.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the Thai government reviewed its
agricultural policies and came to realize the importance of
agriculture in promoting the living standard of farmers and
sustaining the country's development, Ampon said.
</P>
<P>
The government tries to balance the need for strengthening the
country's agricultural competitiveness in the world market and the
need for safeguarding food security.
</P>
<P>
To do so, Ampon said, the national agricultural policies were
divided into two parts. One part focuses on research and
development, seed improvement and products standardization to
promote exports while the other part focuses on infrastructure
development to ensure the basic needs of the farmers.
</P>
<P>
The government is also paying more attention to training
farmers in agricultural technology transfer, he said.
</P>
<P>
Though already the top 10th exporter of agricultural products
in the world, Thailand still needs to improve the quality of
products to expand its market share, Ampon said. "We have to
strengthen research and development, cooperatives system and help
farmers to gain better access to information and technology."
</P>
<P>
Thailand exported rice worth 73.8 billion baht (1.9 billion U.S.
dollars) in 1999, but only 40 percent of its annual crop is of
export grade.
</P>
<P>
Experts say investment in better seed quality and irrigation
could double yields, and hence export revenues.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to decentralize its power and
encourage communities and villages to play more active roles in
agricultural production than before, Ampon said, adding that the
farmers will be more involved in the decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
Being a representative of the Thai government in the
negotiations of the Uruguay round and the World Trade Organization
(WTO) since 1988, Ampon pointed out that though the WTO is
important it is more important for a country to be itself, which
means the country's policies should not be influenced by the rules
of the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care about the WTO rules. Consumer is the king," he
said, adding that the key to expand agricultural exports is to be
more consumer-sensitive and to turn out products which can satisfy
different demands of different consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
