<HEADLINE> 135 Die in Indian Torrential Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- At least 135 people died in the
past three days in incessant rains that savaged Maharashtra,
Gujarat and Andhra Pradesh in southwest India, as army began
rescue operations in marooned areas in Ahmedabad Friday which
received one of the heaviest downpours in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
Maharashtra, which bore the brunt of the rain fury, accounted
for 98 deaths, Andhra Pradesh 22 and Gujarat 15, officials in
state capitals said.
</P>
<P>
In Andhra Pradesh, heavy rains caused breaches to over 100
minor irrigation tanks and 22 people died in various rain-related
incidents, according to the Press Trust of India.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the army has moved in to rescue people from several
marooned areas Ahmedabad, as heavy rains continued to lash several
parts of Gujarat since Thursday, which has claimed 15 lives.
</P>
<P>
Army columns rescued over 3,000 people in Ahmedabad, which bore
brunt of the rains recording 575 mm rainfall, the highest since
1953.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 people living in low-lying areas on the bank of
Sabarmati river were shifted to safer places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
