<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urges Payatas Residents to Get out of Dumpsite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Health authorities
reiterated Friday their appeal to residents of Payatas, Quezon
City of Metro Manila to evacuate the dumpsite lest they get sick
from the fumes being emitted by the huge pile of garbage.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Alberto Romualdez of the Department of Health said
many people staying in the vicinity of the area, where over a
hundred squatters were buried in an avalanche of garbage on Monday
are in danger of inhaling toxic fumes.
</P>
<P>
"Those near the disaster site are in danger. We've advised
local officials and residents to get out of the area," Romualdez
said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Even rescue and health workers in the area, he said, are
allowed to be exposed only from 30 minutes to one hour at a time.
</P>
<P>
Also, Romualdez said he will send a team to check reports that
seepage from Payatas has contaminated Metro Manila's drinking
water source.
</P>
<P>
As of Friday afternoon, the number of people killed in the
dumpsite has climbed to 144 while 60 people were injured,
according to a report of the National Disaster Coordinating
Council (NDCC).
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said rescuers have found 59 survivors in the dumpsite,
adding that 496 families or 2,280 persons have been evacuated to
safe places.
</P>
<P>
However, the council declined to make an estimation on how many
people might still be buried in the avalanche. Some reports said
nearly 200 people remain missing.
</P>
<P>
There were about 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The open
dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in 1999, but the closure was
held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for Quezon City
's more than 700 tons of daily garbage.
</P>
<P>
Due to a week of continuous monsoon rains, the tons of garbage
must have loosened which resulted in its erosion and eventually
became a landslide, said some experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
