<HEADLINE> Canada Willing to Recognize DPRK, Says Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada is willing to officially
recognize the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) as
early as possible, Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy told
Canadian media Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Answering an telephone interview from Ottawa after a meeting of
foreign ministers from G-8 countries in Miyazaki, Japan, Axworthy
disclosed in Tokyo that a decision could come as early as this
weekend after a briefing from a Canadian diplomat touring the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that there was consensus during the meeting
that it was time to take advantage of the momentum of peace after
the recent summit meeting between the North and South of the
Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"We're taking it one step at a time, but what I get from
talking to people in the region is that there is a window here to
open up with North Korea (DPRK). And I believe Canada, as it has
done in many areas around the world, can play a constructive role
in this matter," said Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
The minister is expected to receive a briefing from Margaret
Huber, director-general for North Asia and the Pacific at the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Depending on the outcome of that, I'll be in touch with the
prime minister and we can then decide whether to normalize or not,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Canada has not officially recognized the DPRK since the Korean
War broke out in 1950. 
</P>
</TEXT>
