<HEADLINE> China's T-Bond Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China's treasury bond market rose
this week as all but one bonds picked up by 0.26 yuan on average.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing-based financial advisory company Homeway,
the interest rate on repo transactions corrected as the number of
IPOs decreased over last week.
</P>
<P>
Bond 009905 (3.28 percent, due 2007) and bond 009908 (3.30
percent, due 2009) both picked up by about 0.30 yuan to create new
record highs. Bond 010004 turned out to be a focus on the market
by ending the week at 102.19 yuan, 0.15 yuan above the highest
level of 102.04 yuan that it once briefly touched on June 28. It
was the most active performer on the market this week, boasting
the largest turnover and prospects of further rise through next
week.
</P>
<P>
The three old bonds, 009704, 009905 and 009908, fluctuated
within narrow ranges through this week. Homeway analysts say that
the three bonds may stop slipping because of comparatively high
yields. They predict that the other three bonds listed after 1999
are very likely to continue to move upward in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Since less new stocks were issued this week than in last week,
capital supply on the market was somewhat eased. As a result,
China's repo market stayed quiet for the week. The average
interest rate on repo transactions fell to about 3.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
