<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Suggests State Protection for Key Technologies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A delegate to the ongoing third
national conference of China Intellectual Property Society (CIPS)
today suggested that the country should consider state protection
for key technologies invented by Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Xu Ruide, a senior engineer with Shanghai Hualian
Pharmaceutical Company, proposed that a system of state-owned
patents be introduced, which could effectively safeguard the
country's technological edge and even national security.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, state-owned patented technologies include
those which are funded by the state, transferred from domestic and
overseas individuals, applied by the governmental bodies, and
concerning national secrets.
</P>
<P>
The system of state-owned patents is a supplementary legal
measure for developing countries which have less intellectual
property awareness as well as less economic strength, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
If technological competition among various nations is further
heated, the system could be used by many countries, including
developed ones, the engineer said.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary for China to adjust its patent legal system
for comprehensive protection," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
China in 1985 adopted the patent law, which was revised for the
first time in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the National People's Congress is
amending the revised patent law, which will be fully in line with
the international covenants.
</P>
<P>
Ranked fourth in the world for volume of patents, China had
received one million patent applications by the end of January
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
