<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Hopes More Hostages to Be Released Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Friday that more hostages may be released soon following the
release of another Malaysian national who has been among the
hostages kept by the Abu Sayyaf in Sulu province since April.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference held in the Presidential Palace, Press
Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo Puno said Abdul Jawah
Salawat, who was released Friday morning, will be turned over to
chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado.
</P>
<P>
Puno said Aventajado, who has flown to Zamboanga City, will in
turn entrust the hostage to the Malaysian ambassador to the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf released another Malaysian hostage Zulkarnain
Hashim on June 23. He was among 21 persons, mostly foreigners,
snatched by the group from a diving resort in Malaysia on April 23.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing is certain but there is every hope that it will be
done," Puno said on the possibility of more hostages being
released, adding that "there is a very good chance that in the
next few days, we could see some developments in that area."
</P>
<P>
Puno said there are continuing discussions with the Abu Sayyaf
regarding the release of the hostages pursuant to President Joseph
Estrada's order to Aventajado to ensure first and foremost the
safe release of all captives.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that the government was not aware of any
ransom paid for the Malaysian hostage, adding that the government
will neither sanction nor approve of any ransom payment.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, Philippine President Joseph Estrada told the
visiting foreign ministers of Germany, France and Finland that he
is standing firm on "no-ransom" policy in dealing with the country
's hostage situation.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Estrada briefed the foreign ministers on
the measures the government has taken to solve the problem.
Nationals of the three European countries are among the captives.
</P>
<P>
The president said a military solution to solve the hostage
problem is out of the question, saying that the safety and welfare
of the captives are of paramount concern.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers, on their part, reiterated their full
trust in the Philippine government's handling of the hostage
situation in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the 21 Filipino and foreign hostages taken by the
Abu Sayyaf in April, the group also seized 13 Christian
evangelists who traveled to their camp in Patikul, Sulu to pray
for the hostages on July 1.
</P>
<P>
One German journalist and three French journalists who went
there to interview the original hostages were also reportedly
abducted by the group recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
