<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Have Information Technology University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Two Malaysian companies and
one Singapore company will establish an information technology (IT)
university in Malaysia under a joint venture agreement signed
Friday in Bentong, some 50 kilometers northeast from here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Berjaya Group and Tadmansori Holdings, and Singapore
's Informatic Holdings Ltd signed the agreement, with Malaysian
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad as its witness, to undertake the
project with an initial investment of 10 million ringgit (2.63
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The three parties agreed to take a 30-percent stake each in the
joint venture and a strategic partner will be sought for the
remaining 10 percent stake in the joint venture, for which a new
joint venture company will be formed to run the university.
</P>
<P>
The proposed university to be located at Bukit Tinggi Resort,
Pahang, some 40 kilometers northeast from here will be developed
in two phases with three campuses comprising two physical campuses
and one cyber campus.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, the proposed university would set up a city
campus in Kuala Lumpur and a fully functional cyber campus. Both
campuses would cater to local and international students.
</P>
<P>
The university with a designed capacity to cater for more than
10,000 students will offer a full range of degree and post-
graduate programs including business, IT and engineering,
emphasizing on research and development (R&AMP;D).
</P>
<P>
The first intake will begin in January next year with a target
of 750 students in the first year of operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
