<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Thursday seized a large
quantity of counterfeit goods from hawker-stalls in Kowloon,
according to a customs spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The officers also smashed a pirated discs storage center in the
same district following the seizure of 100,000 HK dollars (12,820
U.S. dollars) worth of pirated CDs, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"For the purpose of eradicating hawker stalls being used for
the sale of counterfeit goods, we have fully cooperated with Food
and Environmental Hygiene Department by means of exchanging
information in those hawkers who have been arrested for selling
counterfeit goods," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Customs has seized 9.4 million HK dollars worth of
counterfeit goods and arrested 230 people with related offenses so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of the year, the officers seized 4.77
million pirated optical discs with a market value of 118 million
HK dollars, and arrested 1,570 suspects.
</P>
<P>
"The Customs will continue to take actions to suppress
counterfeiting and piracy activities to protect the rights of
trade mark owners and preserve the good reputation of the Hong
Kong SAR," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
