<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai A-Shares Surge This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The composite index at the
Shanghai Stock Exchange surged 54.58 points or 2.82 percent over
last week's close to 1987.19 points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing-based financial advisory company Homeway,
trading volume totalled 97.27 billion yuan this week, 109 percent
more than last week's 46.55 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The market remained bullish all the week, setting new highs for
five consecutive trading days.
</P>
<P>
The strong market rally, which started at the end of last week,
continued to be fueled by healthy macroeconomics statistics this
week. Government policies toward software and integrated circuit
industries, initial public offering of China-based Internet
company Sohu.com on the NASDAQ and the an oil price hike also
propelled the market up.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Shanghai composite index closed at a new high.
On the following two days, investors' interest in low-priced State-
owned firms pushed the index to another new high. On Thursday,
iron and steel counters led the market surge in the morning but
were dumped in the afternoon. However, renewed interest in the
Internet-related stock buoyed up the market index again.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, investors turned their interest to the oil-related
stocks after learning the news that oil prices would rose further.
The People's Daily reported on Friday morning that from now on,
prices of gasoline and diesel oil would go up by seven percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Four more firms released their 2000 interim reports this week.
All of them reported considerable growth in profits and earnings
per share in the first half of this year. They are Lucky Film Co.
Ltd, China Southern Glass Holdings Co. Ltd, Tianjin Economic and
Technological Development Area Co. Ltd and Hunan TV and
Broadcasting Intermediary Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai stock market is expected to continue the upward
trend in the next week. However, minor adjustments are inevitable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai B-Shares Rise This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai B-share market
witnessed solid performance propelled by positive earning reports
of several companies on the broader market this week.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing-based financial advisory company Homeway,
the B-share market index shot up 2.49 points or 4.45 percent over
one week ago to 57.35 points at the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 53.34 million Hong Kong dollars for the week,
compared with 55.69 million Hong Kong dollars in last week.
</P>
<P>
Technical trading also contributed to the gains as the market
finally staged a breakout after consolidating for several days in
a trend of the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Figures of robust export growth lifted the market by the
largest margin for the past two weeks on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China's exports rose 38.3 percent in the first half year to 114.
5 billion US dollars, while imports grew by 36.2 percent to 102.1
billion US dollars. Half year trade surplus was about 12 billion
US dollars. June witnessed remarkably strong growth of exports.
Exports surged by nearly 45 percent to a five-month high of 22.2
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's economy also grew at a greater-than-expected rate of 8.
2 percent over the first half year. It is believed that the
country has finally shrugged off the effects of the Asian
financial crisis and is back on the right track.
</P>
<P>
Investors are optimistic about consumption and investment
growth driven by exports in the latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai B-share index is still riding the recent momentum
boosted by positive earnings news and economic fundamentals,
according to Homeway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
