<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Endorse Truce Extension in Aceh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Ambassador and
Permanent Representative to the United Nations Hasan Wirayuda
would endorse an extension of truce between the Indonesian
government and the Free Aceh Movement (GAM), a report reaching
here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the truce, or the Joint Understanding on
Humanitarian Pause in Aceh which took effect on June 2, was
scheduled to expire on August 2.
</P>
<P>
"Right from the start, the three-month term has been adopted
only for periodic evaluation with a view to extending it,"
Wirayuda said in Banda Aceh, capital of Aceh province, adding that
the desire to extend the truce in Aceh does not only come from the
Indonesian government but also from the GAM.
</P>
<P>
"I think the desire to extend the humanitarian pause also comes
from GAM. That is why the Indonesian government and GAM will
continue to meet to asses and evaluate the implementation of the
understanding," Antara news agency quoted Wirayuda as saying.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Indonesian government and the GAM signed
a humanitarian pause accord in Geneva, Switzerland, on May 12,
clearing the way for both sides to ease tension and violent
actions in Aceh province which has claimed hundreds of civilians
and security officers over the past 23 years.
</P>
<P>
The GAM is an underground separatist group in Aceh, the country
's predominantly Muslim province, which has been fighting against
the central government for the province's independence.
</P>
<P>
But Wirayuda said that since the enforcement of the
humanitarian pause on June 2, there has been a significant
decrease in the number of conflicts between the government troops
and the GAM.
</P>
<P>
"I think from the quantitative point of view there has been an
obvious decrease. As far as the reports reaching me from both
sides are concerned, there has been an improvement (in the
situation in Aceh). But stopping it altogether will take time," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam-U.S. BTA Brings Both Opportunities, Challenges: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnam-U.S. bilateral trade
agreement (BTA) will bring about both opportunities and challenges
to Vietnam, a senior Vietnamese trade official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Trade Mai Van Dau said at a press conference
here that the signing of the BTA marks the new development of the
bilateral economic-commercial relations between the two countries
and will contribute to the strengthening of Vietnam-U.S. economic-
commercial ties.
</P>
<P>
It is a success for the Vietnamese party and state's foreign
policy of independence, self-reliance, diversification,
multilateralization and active integration into the regional and
world economy, Dau said.
</P>
<P>
The BTA, covering commodities commerce, services, investment
and intellectual property, will create favorable conditions for
Vietnam to get access to the U.S. market, to absorb U.S.
investment and advanced technology, as well as to join the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
However, the Vietnamese official said, it is a big challenge
that Vietnam has to change a lot of its economic policies in order
to make them conform to WTO rules and to raise competitive ability
of the enterprises and products of the country.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Trade Minister Vu Khoan and U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky signed the Vietnam-U.S.
bilateral trade agreement in Washington on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
