<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Afghans Ordered Released from Detention in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The High Court here Friday
allowed an application for the release of five Afganistans who
were unlawfully detained for seven months at the Kajang prison
near here.
</P>
<P>
Justice Abdul Hamid Mohamad ordered Nisar Ali, Mohamed Basir
Jafari, Mohamed Younes, Abdul Rahim Hamiri and Habibah Fatah to be
released to the Immigration Department for deportation after
allowing their application for a writ of habeas corpus, according
to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
The report said defense counsel Kamarul Hisham Kamaruddin made
the application through an affidavit dated June 1, 2000 on grounds
that the five were detained unlawfully when they were supposed to
be released on January 2, 2000 and deported.
</P>
<P>
The five were first charged in the Sepang Magistrate's Court
under the Passport Act 1966 with entering the country illegally
and the magistrate sentenced them to three months imprisonment
from the date of arrest, November 2, 1999, after they all pleaded
guilty.
</P>
<P>
But the prosecution made an application on December 31, 1999 to
the same magistrate in chambers, in the absence of defense counsel,
to detain the five as witnesses in another case involving an
Iranian, Rahim Amiri Faramarz, believed to have assisted the five
to enter the country illegally. The five, during their
interrogation by immigration officers, repeatedly made statements
of not recognizing Rahim Amiri when his passport photograph was
shown to them.
</P>
<P>
The defense counsel said "The detention order made by the
prosecution under the Criminal Procedure Code was improper and
illegal because it was made in the absence of a counsel."
</P>
<P>
Deputy public prosecutor Hanafiah Zakaria had no objections to
the application for the release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
