<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lijiang River Valleys Being Afforested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- This famous Chinese tourist city of
Guilin, in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region of south China,
has invested 45 million yuan (about 5.42 million U.S. dollars) in
afforesting the valleys of the Lijiang River in the city.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, farmers are now growing trees in
accordance with a design worked out by Beijing Forestry University
and approved by a group of experts organized by the State Forestry
Administration.
</P>
<P>
The afforestation campaign, involving three counties and the
suburbs of Guilin, requires building scenic protection forest
belts along both banks of the river, planting trees on hillsides,
constructing water conservation projects on the upper reaches of
the river and nurseries.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will take three years to finish, and in this
campaign, farmers are expected to grow 11,530 hectares of trees,
said the local sources.
</P>
<P>
Guilin, noted for its natural scenery and strangely shaped
stone formations, hosts some 10 million tourists every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
