<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen B-Share Market Recovers This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen B-share market showed
signs of recovery this week, with the index working steadily back
toward the higher levels in the wake of several earning reports
and the recent technical breakout.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing-based financial advisory company Homeway,
the B-share market index increased 1.94 points or 1.75 percent to
112.50 points at the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 246.93 million Hong Kong dollars for the week, 127.
83 million Hong Kong dollars or 34.11 percent less than last week'
s total.
</P>
<P>
A minor upward extension had generally persisted, with the
overall sentiment favorable about additional gains as the session
progressed.
</P>
<P>
The recent upward momentum was fueled by the latest batch of
economic figures.
</P>
<P>
China's exports rose 38.3 percent in the first half year to 114.
5 billion US dollars, while imports grew by 36.2 percent to 102.1
billion US dollars. Half year trade surplus was about 12 billion
US dollars. June witnessed remarkably strong growth of exports.
Exports surged by nearly 45 percent to a five-month high of 22.2
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's economy also grew at a greater-than-expected rate of 8.
2 percent over the first half year. It is believed that the
country has finally shrugged off the effects of the Asian
financial crisis and is back on the right track.
</P>
<P>
Investors are increasing optimistic about consumption and
investment growth driven by exports in the latter half of the year.
However, follow through interest failed to develop towards the end
of the week amid resumed revenue concerns.
</P>
<P>
The B-share index may have some difficulties in penetrating the
highs on technical basis next week as it works off the overdone
posture generated by the recent 4-day winning streak. But it will
strive to make its way on the plus side as the session progress
under the impact of economic growth, according to Homeway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Launches Awards for Good People Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) on Friday launched Good
People Management Awards to commend employers in achieving good
people management and fostering an employee-oriented culture.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department would be fully committed to promoting an
employee-oriented people management culture, since "good people
management would help bring about harmonious labor relations, a
foundation for Hong Kong's success and prosperity," said
Commissioner for Labor, Pamela Tan Kam Mi-wah, while addressing
the launching ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"The 21st century is marked by rapid development in information
technology," she said, noting that "enterprises in Hong Kong must
have adequate human resources in order to make the best use of
innovative technology."
</P>
<P>
Specifying the awards of the Good People Management Award, Tan
said that as 89 percent of the organizations in Hong Kong are
small and media enterprises (SMEs), the Labor Department "has set
up awards to recognize their outstanding achievement in this area.
"
</P>
<P>
Five awards will be presented to establishments employing 100
or less people, and the other 10 will go to establishments with an
employment size between 101 to 500 and those with 501 and above,
according to her.
</P>
<P>
All non-civil service establishments in Hong Kong are welcome
to join the competition and the entries can be made until
September 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
