<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Amusement Industry Booming (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Each year there are about 350 million people visiting the
amusement parks and places in China and the revenue was about 544
million U.S. dollars in 1999, according to the China Association
of Amusement Parks and Attractions (CAAPA).
</P>
<P>
"China's amusement industry brings along the economic growth,
and the economic growth, in turn, promotes the development of
amusement industry," said Guan Tianchi, vice secretary general of
CAAPA, at the Asian Amusement Expo that closed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
China's amusement industry emerged upon people's demand for
entertainment and recreation activities, with the improvement  of
their living standard after the reform and opening-up.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning, only some simple and individual amusement
facilities were erected separately at the existing parks, but they
brought quite a bit of fun to visitors, said Guan.
</P>
<P>
"As people's requirements were getting higher, they were not
satisfied with this way of fun any more. The new parks and
entertainment places were planned and constructed in the big
coastal cities, starting from the first special economic zone --
Shenzhen near Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
When these new parks were completed, they were well received
with more and more visitors going there for relaxation and
recreation, and that promoted the development of the amusement
industry and made it stronger and stronger, he noted.
</P>
<P>
As the economy grew up continuously in China, amusement parks
extended from coastal to inland areas, from east to west, and from
big cities to medium and small ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Amusement Industry Booming (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guan pointed out that the people's customs and ideology should
be considered in the construction of theme parks, adding that the
theme parks built in China should have Chinese traditional
characteristics and cultural connotation.
</P>
<P>
"Because most visitors to these parks are Chinese, the theme
must be suitable to their taste. Even for foreign visitors, they
would like to enjoy the Chinese traditional culture," he said.
</P>
<P>
With the expansion of the amusement industry, the amusement
facilities, mainly imported from foreign countries at the
beginning, started to be made by Chinese manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
"Because the amusement facilities made in China are less
expensive than foreign ones based on lower costs of labor and
materials, Chinese amusement facilities have a wide domestic
market," said Guan.
</P>
<P>
Regulations on quality standards and quality control for the
amusement facilities have also been enacted and helped improve the
level and quality of design and manufacture of the amusement
facilities, he said, adding that Chinese amusement facilities now
start to be exported to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
In order to develop and manage the amusement industry, the
CAAPA was founded in 1978 and now has over 400 members.
</P>
<P>
CAAPA, which is a member of International Association of
Amusement Parks and Attractions (IAAPA), is taking an active part
in the exchanges of technology and experience with its foreign
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Guan said the Chinese government welcomes foreign investors to
set up enterprises including the amusement facilities
manufacturing companies in China. Some joint-venture for design
and manufacture of the amusement facilities have been set up.
</P>
<P>
"Undoubtedly, using foreign funds and technology to raise our
technical level and employing Chinese staff to reduce the costs
can speed up the amusement industry of China," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Guan said Chinese amusement industry is facing both
opportunities and challenges in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"With the strong economic growth and the steady improvement of
the people's living standard, we are confident that the amusement
industry should have a bright future in China," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
