<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of cultural news stories Xinhua released from July 7 to 13:
</P>
<P>
-- China Launches Children-Song Contest
</P>
<P>
China is launching a nationwide children-song contest to
encourage composers to create more songs for children in the new
century.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of the contest, co-sponsored by the Ministry of
Culture, Central Committee of the Communist Youth League of China,
and the Guangming Daily, is unveiled on July 7 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for receiving new songs is October 30 this year. A
total of 36 prizes will be awarded and the top prize winner is
expected to receive 30,000 yuan (3,430 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
-- China's Film Industry Partly Opens to Overseas Investors
</P>
<P>
China has taken an official and bold step to allow overseas
investors to enter the local film industry, though they are still
not allowed to become the main stake-holders in any local film
company.
</P>
<P>
The reform step was jointly proposed by the State
Administration of Radio, Film and Television and the Ministry of
Culture which recently issued "Some Comments on the Further
Deepening of Reform in the Film Industry."
</P>
<P>
-- World Experts Call for More Careful Protection of Heritage
</P>
<P>
Participants of an international heritage protection symposium
agreed on July 7 that global relics should be well preserved
during the urbanization process.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium, "China -- Cultural Heritage Management
and Urban Development: Challenge and Opportunity," was hosted by
the State Administration of Cultural Heritage, the Ministry of
Construction, the World Bank and the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization in Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Nadam Festival Opens in Inner Mongolia
</P>
<P>
A grand-scale festival, called "Nadam" in Mongolian, was held
at the grasslands of the Hulun Buir League in north China's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Nadam, which means "entertainment and games" in Mongolian, has
a tradition of more than 700 years. Throughout the history of the
event, horse racing, archery and Mongolian wrestling have been
three major activities.
</P>
<P>
Track and field events, ball sports, art performances and photo
shows were also included in this year's Nadam Festival.
</P>
<P>
-- Rare Ethnic Clothing Exhibited in SW Province
</P>
<P>
A skirt made of six detachable layers, the shortest of which is
a mere 20 cm, is being shown at the First Chinese Nationalities
Costume Exposition in this capital city of Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The unique black mini-to-full-length skirt, made by the Miao
ethnic group in the Leixian County in Guizhou Province of
southwest China, is collected by the Beijing Palace of Ethnic
Culture.
</P>
<P>
-- Writers Donate to Literary Foundation
</P>
<P>
Four well-known writers who won the first Lao She Literary
Prize have donated money they earned from book sales to the Lao
She Literary and Art Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The foundation granted the literary prize for the first time in
June and published a compilation of all the winning short novels,
written by Tie Ning, Liu Heng, Ye Guangqin, Lu Tao and Mu Guozheng.
</P>
<P>
Following the book's release, Tie, Liu, Ye and Lu endowed 12,
000 yuan (1,446 U.S. dollars) worth of remuneration of the first
edition to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
-- Encyclopedias Donated to Poverty-Relieve Program
</P>
<P>
Three leading cultural organs presented on July 11 copies of
the Abridged Encyclopedia Britannica to libraries in 50 poor
counties in west China.
</P>
<P>
The move, as part of the country's poverty-relieve program, was
initiated by the China Poverty-Relieve Committee of Culture, the
Ministry of Culture and the Encyclopedia of China Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
The cultural committee, founded in 1993, has launched a
massive program, "Ten Thousand Village Libraries", to improve
library facilities in the poor areas. So far, as many as 60,000
village libraries have been set up with its help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel now appears to have enough natural gas to
provide for all its needs through 2025, the National Infrastructure
Ministry's chief geologist said this week.
</P>
<P>
In an internal document submitted by the ministry to Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Finance Minister Avraham Shochat, Dr.
Yehezkel Druckman recommended that Israel not purchase natural gas
form Egypt, because Israel's reserves of natural gas from offshore
drilling are likely to reach 100 billion cubic meters in the next
three to four years and 150 billion cubic meters within a decade.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) would take part in
any oil production increase to be adopted by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), said UAE Oil Minister Obeid
Bin Saif Al Nasir on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
All oil producing countries will share in the production hike
once OPEC favours it. However, the decision to raise oil production
quota by the member states should be taken after consultations
among OPEC countries, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
OPEC was keen to stabilize world oil market, he said, expressing
hope that crude oil price per barrel could remain between 22 and 28
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Unemployment in Israel continued its downward slide
in June, reaching 8.8 percent, or 209,460 people, according to the
latest figures released by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The numbers confirm the impression that there is now a steady,
if slow, drop in the numbers of the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
In the last four months of 1999, unemployment was at 9.1
percent, up from 9 percent in August 1999 and 8.9 percent in June
and July of last year.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The Palestinian Development and Investment Company
(PDICO) planned to invest about 2 billion U.S. dollars in tourism,
real estate, energy, transport and information technology sectors
in the Palestinian self-rule areas in the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
PDICO General Manager Farouk Zeitar was quoted by the London-
based Arabic-language Al-Haiyat daily as saying that his firm had
invested a total of 530 million U.S. dollars in Palestine.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in Nablus on Tuesday that PDICO's next Five-
Year Plan was designed to heavily fund infrastructure projects to
help boost Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned previous activities undertaken by PDICO,
including the establishment of some industrial zones at a cost of
210 million to 212 million dollars in the Palestinian territories
over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
PDICO was considering the establishment of a holding company to
construct more industrial zones. The company will have a capital of
50 million dollars, 30-35 percent of which will be offered for
public subscription, he added.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel stands to gain another 9.3 billion U.S.
dollars from trade with its Arab neighbors in the event a peace
agreement is reached, according to a new study. These "peace
dividends" would be earned by taking advantage of the countries'
geographic proximity.
</P>
<P>
The report, written by Niron Hashai of Tel Aviv University,
assumes that all economic and political trade barriers are removed
between Israel and Jordan, Syria and Egypt. Trade barriers include
lack of formal relations, tariffs, quotas and anything else which
hinders the free flow of goods between borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
