<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Enforce Hygiene Rules for Lake Victoria Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is to
enforce hygiene regulations for all beaches in the Lake Victoria
region in southwestern Kenya, Kisumu District Commissioner Andrew
Mondoh has said.
</P>
<P>
Mondoh said the government will ensure all the beaches are
clean and complied with the public health regulations, and the
Fishery Department has planned rapid clean-up of the beaches along
the Lake Victoria, the East African Standard newspapers Friday
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner made the remarks at the recent celebration to
mark the World Population Day at Kisumu City, saying his
government has set aside 18 million shillings (about 234,000 U.S.
dollars) for the improvement of sanitation along Lake Victoria
beaches.
</P>
<P>
Lake Victoria region is Kenya's key fishing place. Due to
hygiene problems, the European Union (EU) imposed a ban on fish
products from the country in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to Kenyan Planning Minister Gideon Ndambuki, Kenya
had lost 3.4 billion shillings (about 44 million dollars) since
the ban was imposed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Kenya exported about 52,000 tons of fish, mostly Nile
perch from Lake Victoria , valued at 862 million shillings, to EU,
mainly to Germany and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industry Backs on Track in Czech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Industrial production of the Czech
Republic has posted a 6.5-percent increase in May 2000, the
fastest this year, showing a recovery of the country's bog-down
industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures released on Thursday by Czech's
national statistics bureau, the first five months have seen an
industrial growth of 4.8 percent over the corresponding period of
1999.
</P>
<P>
Amid a global stagnancy in economy, industry output dropped 3.1
percent in 1999 in this European country.
</P>
<P>
To reverse the situation, the Czech government has adopted
measures to stimulate the industry including the attraction of
foreign investment, promotion of medium- and small-sized
enterprises and encouragement of exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
