<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chongqing Residents Buy Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- More and more residents in
Chongqing are buying homes, and in the first five months this year
over 90 percent of new housing went to private home owners in this
southwest China municipality.
</P>
<P>
According to local statistics, 927,000 sq m of new housing was
sold in the five months, up about 80 percent from a year earlier,
and 91 percent of new homes were bought by private individuals.
</P>
<P>
"The housing reform that started in the second half of 1998
has boosted home buying in the city," said You Shicheng, deputy
chief of the Chongqing Land and Real Estate Management Bureau.
</P>
<P>
China overhauled its public welfare housing system in 1998,
which ended the distribution of public housing to employees in
urban areas. The government now encourages urban residents to buy
homes while continuing to provide low-rent housing for the needy.
</P>
<P>
As the reform moves forward, more and more residents will
become home owners, You said. To meet the demand, the city's
investment in housing is rising at an annual rate of 30 percent,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Reports Double-Digit Industrial Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong
Province in south China, reported a 17.3 percent industrial growth
in the first six months of this year, compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the statistics bureau of Guangzhou said that the
city accomplished 147.44 billion yuan (about 17.76 billion U.S.
dollars) in output value from January to June.
</P>
<P>
Industries contributed 57.1 percent to the city's gross
domestic product (GDP) and 96.4 percent of the locally
manufactured goods were marketed, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the city also delivered 36.8 billion
yuan (about 4.43 billion U.S. dollars) worth of commodities for
export.
</P>
<P>
A local official in charge of economic affairs explained that
the city has stepped up efforts to reorganize assets and transform
the operational system in enterprises since the beginning of the
year. State-owned enterprises of the city have also achieved
success in reducing losses and getting rid of financial
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
But large and medium-sized enterprises and overseas-financed
ventures continued to be the key driving force behind Guangzhou's
fast industrial growth, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the city's industrial growth this year would
be above 14.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
