<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traces of South China Tiger Found in Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese zoologists have found
traces of the South China tiger in a dense primitive forest in
Chongqing Municipality, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that traces of the tiger have been
discovered in Chongqing in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year traces of the endangered animal were found in
Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces, east China.
</P>
<P>
According to Deng Heli, who recently headed a team of
zoologists to investigate wild animals in the region, the
scientists confirmed that the 20-sq-cm footprints found in a dense
forest in Daba Mountain, Chengkou County, were left by a hungry
South China tiger.
</P>
<P>
Local farmer Xia Zhiyou said he saw a footprint suspected to be
left by a South China tiger in neighboring Shaanxi Province in
November last year, and found part of a shank bone of a small
animal in the dung nearby.
</P>
<P>
Local villagers also reported to the scientists that they saw a
tiger and two cubs walk around in the forest in the spring of 1998.
The tigers ran away at the sight of the villagers, they said.
</P>
<P>
The South China tiger is listed as one of the ten most
endangered species in the world. It is estimated that there are
only 20 to 30 such tigers in the wild. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
