<HEADLINE> Russian Defense Chief Opposes Reorganizing Missile Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev on Friday blasted the proposed reorganization of the
country's strategic missile force, branding the plan as imbecility
and a crime against Russia.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev, accompanying President Vladimir Putin on a visit to
Nizhny Tagil to attend an arms show in central Russia, threatened
to step down if the plan goes ahead.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to proposals advanced by the General Staff
that the strategic force cease to be a service and become
subordinate to the central defense authority or even to the air
force command.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said he would not preside over the attempts at
destroying the strategic missile force, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Ground-based missiles make up the strongest defense against a
nuclear attack and cannot be sidelined, he said, adding that the
strategic missile force is the core of the country's recently
adopted military doctrine.
</P>
<P>
If the force is done away with, so should the new doctrine, the
defense chief said.
</P>
<P>
The attempts at this kind of reorganization are "criminal
stupidity and an attack on Russia's national interests to the same
degree," Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
He said the General Staff is suggesting exactly what the
Americans want to build into START-3, he said. "Whose interests is
the General Staff, thought to be the brainpower of the armed
forces, promoting?"
</P>
<P>
"Whoever is not indifferent to the future of Russia, the
security of its people and its position in the world," must join
the debate on reorganization of the strategic missile force, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
