<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- In most Chinese provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities, around 60 percent of all public houses have been
sold to individuals, and the proportion surpassed 80 percent in
Chongqing Municipality, and the provinces of Zhejiang, Henan and
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, according to Nie Meisheng,
director of the Housing Industrialization Promotion Center under
the Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
-- China's business climate index rose to its highest level of
the past seven quarters in the second quarter of this year,
according to the figures from the National Bureau of Statistics.
It shows that the index rose to 121.7 points by the end of June, 6.
5 points higher than at the end of March and 11.8 points higher
than one year ago.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council has mapped out a series of new policies to
encourage IT development and raise its creativity and
competitiveness on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The policies consisting of 53 articles in 13 chapters are meant
to boost the country's software and integrated circuit (IC)
sectors.
</P>
<P>
-- During a meeting with a delegation from Taiwan's New Party,
Li Yafei, secretary-general of the Beijing-based Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits, said that under the one-China
principle, both sides of the Taiwan Straits have equal weight in
consultations to discuss the reunification issue.
</P>
<P>
-- Twenty-seven out of the approximately 15,000 registered
websites in China have been chosen to pilot on-line advertising,
the State Administration of Industry and Commerce announced. These
websites, including www.sohu.com, www.netease.net and etang.com,
are selected for being "well-established" and all of them are
registered in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
-- The area planted with tobacco in China this year decreased
to nearly one million hectares, down by 16,000 hectares over last
year. The inventories of tobacco in the country also decreased to
three billion kilograms, 725 million kg less than that in 1998,
according to a report from the State Tobacco Monopoly
Administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
