<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- China Intellectual Property Society convened its third
national conference and the 2000 academic symposium in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- The total turnover of China's interbank money market
amounted to 718.9 billion yuan (about 86.6 billion U.S. dollars)
in the first half year, up 246 percent from a year earlier,
according to the China Interbank Center based in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
-- China's central government has approved the plan of setting
up a satellite telecommunication operator -- ChinaSat to further
break up the market monopoly of the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
-- A tornado in east China's Jiangsu Province has left 11
people dead and 500 others injured. The tornado hit Yangzhou and
Taizhou cities in the province Thursday, destroying more than 4,
000 houses and uprooting big trees.
</P>
<P>
-- China's first pop music hall has been set up in the Chinese
capital of Beijing. This indicates that the status of pop music as
an art has been further confirmed in the country. Before this, pop
singers usually performed in discos and karaoke clubs, with some
top-rated ones occasionally singing at TV shows.  
</P>
