<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet:
</P>
<P>
-- The European Union (EU) would provide financial aid to Turkey
from its 2001 budget, Guenther Verheugen, commissioner responsible
for EU Enlargement Affairs, told Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem in Ankara on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen said that the amount would be determined in accordance
with Turkey's harmonization process to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Istanbul suffered the hottest day in history on Thursday with
a daily average temperature of 42.7 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the temperature was felt much higher, at
around 48 degrees Celsius, due to the high humidity rate.
</P>
<P>
Extremely high temperatures were effective particularly on the
same day all across the country.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet:
</P>
<P>
-- The rapprochement between Turkey and Greece has also been
reflected on Turkish Lira (TL), as the Turkish currency, for the
first time in history, started being sold at the Foreign Exchange
Offices in Athens.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the TL was only sold for the time being, and
full interactions over the TL will soon get started.
</P>
<P>
Yenibinyil:
</P>
<P>
-- The European Union (EU) decided to lift the quotas imposed on
Turkish textile starting as of 2002 until the year of 2005 in
stages.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials said that Turkish textile sector should take
advantage of this opportunity to re-structure itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
