<HEADLINE> Another Malaysian Hostage Released by Philippine Armed Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The armed group that abducted
21 people in Sipadan off Sabah, East Malaysia, on April 24 has
released another Malaysian hostage who is policeman Abdul Jawah
Salawat, Bernama news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The release was confirmed by Malaysian Ambassador to the
Philippines Mohamed Arshad M. Hussain who said Philippine
government negotiators had informed him of the matter Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I received a call from (Philippine government chief negotiator
Robert) Aventajado today informing me about the release of another
Malaysian," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Jawah is expected to be officially handed over to the
ambassador by the negotiation team in Zamboanga, the Philippines,
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"After that, the Malaysian embassy will make the necessary
arrangements to send him home," the ambassador said, adding "I
have spoken with him (Abdul Jawah) over the telephone and he is
fine. I will be going to Zamboanga to receive him tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador expressed relief and happiness over the release
of the second Malaysian hostage, saying he was optimistic that
this would eventually lead to the freeing of the other hostages.
</P>
<P>
The abductors released the first Malaysian Zulkarnain Hashim, a
ranger with the Sabah Wildlife Department, on June 23.
</P>
<P>
The armed group in the southern Philippines is still holding 19
of the Sipadan hostages comprising seven Malaysians, three Germans,
two French nationals, two Finns, two South Africans, two Filipinos
and a Lebanese. 
</P>
