stance on maintaining good relations with Uganda and Rwanda and
its continued efforts to find lasting peace in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The independent Guardian newspaper Friday quoted Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye as saying that Tanzania will continue to be
involved in the peace-seeking efforts in the Great Lakes Region
and would like to maintain a neutral stance over countries that
have deployed troops in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye made the remarks Thursday during a parliament debate in
the central town of Dodoma, at which a shadow minister said Uganda
and Rwanda were looting minerals in the DRC on the pretext of
defending their security interests.
</P>
<P>
"This is not Tanzania's position," said the premier referring
to the shadow minister's remarks, warning that such "sensitive
statements" could threaten Tanzania's relationship with its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said Tanzania still maintains good and brotherly
relationship with Uganda and Rwanda and is involved in efforts to
find solutions for ending the on-going conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tanzanian Acting Foreign Minister Bakari Mwapachu
said in a budget speech that the country maintains good
relationship with all neighboring countries, noting that there is
good cooperation in various fields such as economic activities,
social area, culture and defense and security.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the wars in the DRC and Burundi have slowed
down the growth of trade relations between Tanzania and the two
countries. 
</P>
