<HEADLINE> World's Fourth Largest Mining Giant to Invest in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Billiton Group, the fourth largest
mining company in the world, is making feasibility studies on co-
building an ore-dressing plant with an annual output of 250,000
tons of metallic zinc in southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The group has signed an agreement with the Yunnan Lanping
Nonferrous Metals Company Ltd., which is in charge of China's
largest lead-zinc mine at Lanping of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
The Lanping mine, in northwestern Yunnan, ranks third in the
world in verified reserves of zinc and lead. China has been making
preparations for its development in the past two decades. However,
the lack of funds and up-to-date expertise is a problem.
</P>
<P>
Billiton has been attracted by the mine after it made
extensive investigations. It set up a representative office in
Kunming, the provincial capital, in 1998 and formed a joint
venture with an enterprise of the Department of Geology and
Mineral Resources of the Yunnan Province government in June last
year.
</P>
<P>
Initial investment for the development of the mine is estimated
at 500 million U.S. dollars. Billiton will hold 65 percent of the
stake.
</P>
<P>
Negel Clark, general manager of Billiton in China, said the
feasibility studies are expected to be completed at the end of the
year. It will reduce the risk to the minimum extent.  
</P>
