<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia to Improve Housing for Herdsmen, Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The government of Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region in north China has decided to build 140 million
square meters of brick-concrete houses in the coming six years for
poor farmers and herdsmen who are living in low, dark wickiups or
tents.
</P>
<P>
At least 2.3 million farmer and herdsman families will benefit
from the government aid-the-poor housing project.
</P>
<P>
The regional government also plans to accelerate the
construction of a number of towns and cities, which is expected to
stimulate the consumption of building materials, metallurgical and
chemical products, and furniture and in the end promote local
economic development.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that an average farmer or herdsman in
Inner Mongolia has only eight square meters of brick-concrete
house, far below the standard of 15 square meters for comfortable
living set by the government.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the money needed to build these
houses will mainly come from farmers or herdsmen themselves,
supported by bank loans. And the government will help reduce the
cost of housing construction and be responsible for roads, and
water and electricity supply and other infrastructure facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
