<HEADLINE> Science Facilities Attract Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese tourists have become more
and more interested in visiting science-related sites, such as
observatories, space navigation centers, botanical gardens,
research institutes and laboratories.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's largest municipality, a dozen of science
and technology promotion sites including the city's observatory,
and aerospace equipment plant, have opened to tourists.
</P>
<P>
In Shenyang, capital of Liaoning Province in northeast China, a
center for popularization of space science has received more than
20,000 visitors over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The country's A-bomb and H-bomb research and production center
in Sichuan Province, southwest China, has attracted hundreds of
thousands of tourists since it was partly opened to visitors early
last year.
</P>
<P>
In the southernmost island province of Hainan, the Chinese
Academy of Tropical Agriculture has a botanical garden with 1,200
kinds of tropical plants. Last year alone, more than 350,000
tourists visited the garden.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the growing zeal for tours to science
facilities to the country's prosperous scientific and
technological development in recent years.
</P>
<P>
To meet the market demand, many Chinese travel services have
designed science tour programs. Even the country's top research
body, the Chinese Academy of Science, has established a travel
service specialized in providing expedition tour programs.
</P>
