<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman to Accelerate WTO Accession Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Oman's accession to the World
Trade Organization (WTO) could have been speeded up had some key
legislations not taken more time, said a senior official of the
world body.
</P>
<P>
There was also lack of expertise on some subjects such as
customs evaluation, the Dubai-based Gulf News daily Friday quoted
Cato Adrian, WTO's counsellor in the accession division, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Oman has met all of the WTO requirements, Adrian said
over the phone from Geneva that a patent law has yet to be enacted
along with some legislations concerning intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
The working group's sixth meeting held in Geneva last week has
approved Oman's WTO membership which is to be formalized by the
137-nation trade body.
</P>
<P>
Oman's accession to the WTO could be considered fast enough when
compared to Saudi Arabia, which is still waiting in the long queue,
although the kingdom applied for membership in mid-1993, while all
the other Arab Gulf states are WTO members.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 32 applicants, including Oman, in the
queue for WTO membership.
</P>
<P>
Adrian also expected China to become a member by the year-end,
while it will take at least 30 months for Yemen, Oman's neighbour
in the south, to join the fold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
