<HEADLINE> Abu Sayyaf Releases Another Malaysian Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The extremist Abu Sayyaf group
holding some 40 hostages in Sulu province in the southern
Philippines released one Malaysian hostage early Friday morning,
said a report of the local ABS-CBN television.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the development was announced by Sulu
Governor Abdusakur Tan, who identified the Malaysian national as
Abdul Juwan Sulawat, adding that the release was facilitated by
Presidential Advisor on Mindana Affairs Lee Peng Wee.
</P>
<P>
The release came after backdoor negotiations to seek the
release of a German journalist and eight Malaysians held by the
Abu Sayyaf group gained ground last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf abducted 21 Filipino and foreign hostages in a
diving resort in Malaysia on April 23 and taken them to Sulu
province.
</P>
<P>
The rebels released one Malaysian hostage last month in what
officials described as a "goodwill gesture."
</P>
<P>
However, the Abu Sayyaf seized 13 Christian evangelists who
traveled to their camp in Patikul, Sulu, on July 1.
</P>
<P>
One German journalist and three French journalists who went
there to interview the original hostages were also reportedly
abducted by the group recently.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada told the visiting foreign
ministers of Germany, France and Finland Thursday that he is
standing firm on "no-ransom" policy in dealing with the country's
hostage situation.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Estrada briefed the foreign ministers on
the measures the government has taken to solve the problem.
Nationals of the three European countries are among the captives.
</P>
<P>
The president said a military solution to solve the hostage
problem is out of the question, saying that the safety and welfare
of the captives are of paramount concern.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also expressed confidence over the release soon of the
hostages, citing favorable developments in the ongoing
negotiations with the Abu Sayyaf captors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
