<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Funds Malawi, Kenya for Fishery Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) has granted Malawi and Kenya 344,000 U.S.
dollars to upgrade the quality of fishery products in the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) region, Zambian
newspaper Times reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at improving fishery products in the
COMESA region to meet international standards and furthermore to
facilitate export.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, in collaboration with FAO, assisted selected fish
processing plants in Malawi and Kenya to apply quality assurance
program based on the Hazard Analysis Critical Control Points.
</P>
<P>
The assistance at each fish processing plant included examining
its compliance with regulations stipulated by the European Union (
EU) and other relevant health hygiene regulations for fish and
fishery products on packaging.
</P>
<P>
Once the quality of fish and fishery products improved more
fish would be processed for the export market within and outside
the COMESA region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
