<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Vaccine Tested in Uganda Promising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The HIV vaccine being tested in
east African country Uganda has shown the potential to protect
human beings against infection, the New Vision daily reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory results showed that HIV virus had been killed in the
blood taken from vaccinated individuals, Professor Roy Mugerwa,
Ugandan coordinator of the vaccine trial, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said though the vaccine had been tailored to the HIV-1 sub-
type B that is most common in Europe and America, preliminary
results indicate that it would protect against the A and B sub-
types that are most common in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The professor said that 20 percent of the 40 vaccinated
individuals had shown signs of resistance to HIV, adding that the
figure appeared low but could be improved.
</P>
<P>
The results were presented to the International AIDS Conference
Thursday in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"What has been shown is that this vaccine is able to produce an
immune response in about 20 percent of the cases, and also shown
potential to protect against HIV regardless of which sub-types of
the virus is circulating in the population," Mugerwa was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Mugerwa said while they continue to monitor the vaccine
recipients for another year, they are looking for funds for the
second phase of trial on a larger number of patients.
</P>
<P>
Forty volunteers are participating in the trial of the HIV
vaccine, a collaboration between three Ugandan institutions and a
U.S. University, which is funded by the U.S. National Institute of
Allergy and Infectious Diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
