<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Urges International Community to Help Solve Refugee Problems  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye has appealed to the international community to
help the eastern African country solve the worsening refugee
problem.
</P>
<P>
The independent Guardian newspaper Friday quoted him as saying
that the refugees fled from neighboring countries are causing a
lot of problems to Tanzania and the government was spending its
meager resources to strengthen security in several western regions
that shelter refugees.
</P>
<P>
Speaking with visiting Canadian Minister of International
Cooperation Maria Minna in the central town of Dodoma on Thursday,
Sumaye said initially his government thought that the problem
would not take long to be solved, but it now appears that the
solution is far from being found.
</P>
<P>
He told the Canadian minister that although his government is
striving to restore peace in the Great Lakes region, it is
difficult to tell how long Tanzania will go on to accommodate the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
He said most refugees were going into villages from the camps,
causing problems to the local people as they are forced to share
the little resources available.
</P>
<P>
However, it is difficult to tell who is a refugee and who is
not since Tanzanians living in borders share the same language and
customs as those living in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Tanzanian Minister for Home Affairs Muhammad
Khatib told the parliament that Tanzania is currently sheltering
around 664,000 refugees from Burundi, Rwanda, the Democratic
Republic of the Congo and Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
