<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tea Output Drops in Central Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The prevailing cold and dry
weather has caused a drastic drop in tea output in Central
Province, Kenya, local media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Most factories in the province are processing half their
regular share of tea leaves due to a massive frost swept across
some districts last week, the East African Standard newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
G.K.Njoroge, a local tea manager, said local tea factories are
receiving an average of 18,000 kg of green leaf down from 80,000
kg under normal weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
In Nyeri District, an official from the Kenya Tea Board said
production has dropped to the lowest level and there are
possibilities of some tea factories closing down until September
when weather conditions are expected to improve.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper reported that the severe frost also
destroyed maize and coffee crops. Coffee berries in Nyeri has
fallen off prematurely and maize plants had dried up in cold
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
District agriculture and livestock extension officer J.T.
Muchoki said the bad weather had forced them to revise the
expected harvest this season, and "we expected a harvest of 20
bag of maize (90 kg per bag) per hectare which we have later
revised to 10 bags."
</P>
<P>
Provincial Commissioner Peter Kiilu said about 800,000 people
in the province were faced with famine and needed urgent relief
food because of the cold and dry weather. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
