<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Troops Admit Chemical Dumping into S.Korean River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Forces Korea (USFK) Friday
admitted that its headquarters at the Yongsan compound in the
central Seoul dumped toxic chemicals into the Han River.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the USFK confirmed that its Yongsan
compound released 20 gallons (75.7 liters) of formaldehyde last
February.
</P>
<P>
The chemical was put through a series of waste treatment and is
believed to have been diluted to cause no damage to the
environment, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Prime Minister Lee Han-dong Friday said his
government will ask the USFK to take steps to prevent recurrence
of chemical waste dumping.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Korean environment groups held a protest
rally in front of the Yongsan military compound, demanding a
formal apology from the USFK commander and the U.S. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The Green Korea United (GKU) said it will take the matter to
the G-8 conference in Okinawa and will take steps to receive an
apology from the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference Thursday, the GKU accused the USFK of
secretly discharging some 480 bottles of solution mixed with
formalin and methanol into Han River which passes through the
middle of the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The GKU showed as evidence photos, empty bottles and remaining
solution at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
Formalin and methanol are poisonous chemicals that can lead to
mental unrest and memory loss if a person is exposed for a few
hours. Long-term exposure can kill fish and other marine living
things.
</P>
<P>
The USFK is said to have used the chemicals in preserving the
corpses of its servicemen who died from various accidents in South
Korea before repatriation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
