<HEADLINE> China's First Naturally-Bred White Crane in Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A couple of white cranes in the
safari park in Hefei, capital of east China's Anhui Province, have
hatched out a baby white crane from one of three eggs they had
laid.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time white cranes in captivaty naturally bred.
The country used to breed the rare birds by artificial
insemination in Beijing Zoo.
</P>
<P>
White cranes are native to Siberian areas of Russia and fly
south in winter to the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze
River of China, the northern parts of India and Iran, according to
breeders in the safari park.
</P>
<P>
Wild white cranes in China now number about 2,700 and the
captive ones are only 40.
</P>
<P>
The rare species is under the first-class protection in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
