<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Four Chinese cities -- Beijing,
Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan and Hohhot, reported slight air pollution
today, with the highest reading at 136 for Taiyuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center today, level-two, or fairly good
air quality, was found in 33 cities: Tianjin, Shenyang, Dalian,
Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou,
Wenzhou, Hefei, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao,
Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Changsha, Guangzhou, Shantou, Zhanjiang, Nanning,
Haikou, Chongqing, Chengdu, Guiyang, Xi'an, Lanzhou, Xining,
Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulate matter less than 10 microns in size was the major
pollutant in most of the cities, except Changsha, Guangzhou,
Nanning, Chongqing and Guiyang, where sulfur dioxide was the major
air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Yantai, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Kunming and Lhasa reported excellent
air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution readings: not
exceeding 50), level-two or fairly good (pollution readings: 51 to
100), level-three or slightly polluted (pollution readings: 101-
200), level-four or poor (pollution readings: 201 to 300) and
level-five or hazardous (pollution readings: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
