<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat held their first bilateral meeting late Wednesday
night without making progress on any of the core issues, Israeli
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They described the hour-long meeting, which was also attended by
several advisers from each side, as tough going, and said the Camp
David summit, which enters its fourth day Friday, will probably
last at least another week.
</P>
<P>
Among the ideas said to be floated in earnest is one that would
give the Palestinians land in Israel so as to enable Israel to
maintain control of settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel will make a "substantial" contribution to a new
international organization which will be set up to compensate and
rehabilitate Palestinian refugees, and will absorb tens of
thousands of them as part of a "family reunification" program on a
humanitarian basis, Israeli officials at Camp David revealed.
</P>
<P>
According to a program reportedly presented by Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak to the Camp David summit, Israel will also not
object to the Palestinians referring to these moves as a "
realization of the right of return," so long as no further demands
on Israel are made in this context.
</P>
<P>
Barak will stress, officials said, that Israel refuses to
recognize the Palestinians' right of return home, and will not
accept legal or moral responsibility for creating the refugee
problem, beyond expressing sorrow for their suffering.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- After a series of last-minute false alarms and arguing over
fine print, the Israel Medical Association and the Treasury
Thursday night signed an agreement of principles ending the 127-day
doctors strike.
</P>
<P>
During the last two days of negotiations, the two sides agreed
that the overall wage hike for doctors will be 13.2 percent, which
is about NIS 280 million (about 68.5 million U.S. dollars). Other
still-unresolved wage issues will be arbitrated.
</P>
<P>
In return for the arbitration accord, the doctors agreed to
relinquish their right to strike for a period of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- In an emotional ceremony at Israel's presidential residence,
former President Ezer Weizman and his wife Reuma bid farewell to
the staff that served them during his seven years in office
Thursday and set out for their home in Caesarea.
</P>
<P>
"I have left many jobs in my life, and it's difficult to say
goodbye to the people who have been a part of your life, but this
is the last job I will ever have to leave," Weizman told his staff.
He was forced to leave the post early because of financial
irregularities and subsequent police investigation.
</P>
<P>
Likud legislator Reuven Rivlin will serve as interim president
until Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg returns home from the United
States Friday. Burg will serve until a new president, elected by
secret ballot in the parliament July 31, is sworn in on August 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
