<HEADLINE> Opposition's Bid to Force Early Election Illegal: Zimbabwean Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
dismissed calls by the opposition Movement for Democratic Change (
MDC) for the President to step down and pave way for early
presidential elections, local media reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
It would be unlawful for civic groups and the MDC to try and
force early presidential election, Minister of Information, Posts
and Telecommunications Chen Chimutengwende said in a statement on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chimutengwende made the statement in response to a story
published on Thursday's issue of the Financial Gazette which said
the MDC and civic groups would embark on unspecified mass action
to force early election.
</P>
<P>
"Presidential election is scheduled for the year 2002. It would
be totally unacceptable and illegal for the civic groups and the
MDC to organize mass action, anarchy and violence in order to
force the presidential election to be held now instead of the year
2002," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Chimutengwende said if the groups went ahead with their plan,
security forces would be called in to "deal ruthlessly" with the
people involved.
</P>
<P>
The minister said previous mass action has led to anarchy and
destruction, adding that any party that wished to change the law
should do so through Parliament.
</P>
<P>
He called for the opposition to be constructive for the socio-
economic development of the country, rather than be used by
outside forces to destroy the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
