<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean White Farmers Given Ultimatums to Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Some white commercial farmers in
Zimbabwe have been given up to a week to leave their farms or face
massive disruption of farming operations by war veterans in the
country, The Herald newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ultimatums come just days before the launch of the
government-sponsored resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
President of the Commercial Farmers Union Tim Henwood Thursday
said about 50 farmers had been served with ultimatums to vacate
their farms.
</P>
<P>
Henwood said the situation on the farms was "too dangerous" as
the war veterans had threatened to attack farmers who refused to
comply with the orders to leave the farms.
</P>
<P>
"They have threatened to kill all farmers who do not get off
the land within their specified period. Although I know of 50
affected farmers now, the situation is spreading throughout the
country," He said.
</P>
<P>
The president noted he had been assured by the police that they
would deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
"We now await to see the action to be taken by the police to
stop the marauding war veterans causing problems on the farms. The
police have promised that they will bring the situation under
control," he said, adding that the disruption of farming
activities would have serious implications on crop production and
the country's food security.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans have occupied about 1,500 white-owned
commercial farms since February to press for the equitable
redistribution of land to the majority of landless Zimbabweans.
</P>
</TEXT>
