<HEADLINE> Drug Trafficking to Be on Rise in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Drug trafficking and abuse have
been increasing in Zambia, making the country both a transit and a
consumer of drugs, Zambian newspaper "the Post" Friday quoted an
anti-drug official as saying .
</P>
<P>
Drug Enforcement Commissioner Raphael Mungole said on Thursday
that trafficking in heroin and its abuse has become common in the
country and addiction levels would soon outstrip rehabilitation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
According to the commissioner, the problem has been compounded
by Zambia's geographical position and the centrality of the Lusaka
International Airport which makes the country easy to access by
dealers.
</P>
<P>
"The mandrax consignments which are smuggled into South Africa
are exchanged with groceries, motor vehicles and other household
goods which are transported to Zambia in big tracks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Drug Enforcement Commission (DEC) statistics reveal that
between January and June this year, drugs worth 34 billion kwacha
(about 11.3 million U.S. dollars) had been seized.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner disclosed that Zambia's drugs mainly come from
India, Pakistan and Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
