<HEADLINE> Share Prices Turn Upward in Tokyo on Bargain Hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in Tokyo
Friday for the first time in four trading days on bargain hunting
following previous declines.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 106.00 points, or 0.62
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 17,142.90 after losing
more than 530 points over the previous three days.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 5.70 points or 0.36 percent to 1,579.
86.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 741.11 million
shares from Thursday's 789.97 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The banking and construction sectors rebounded after taking
heavy losses Thursday by the failure of department-store operator
Sogo Co.
</P>
<P>
Sogo, which has been put to the Tokyo market's liquidation post,
was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information and technology issues were boosted by
Thursday's gains on New York's Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
Gainers also included the rubber, nonferrous metal and air-
transportation sectors, while the real-estate, insurance and drug
sectors faced selling.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outpaced
losers 666 to 588, while 144 issues closed unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
