<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oceania Soccer President Steps Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealander who stunned
the footballing world by abstaining from the recent FIFA World Cup
hosting vote has announced his immediate retirement as president
of the Oceania Football Confederation (OFC).
</P>
<P>
Charlie Dempsey caused an international furor over his decision
to abstain from the final crucial vote, effectively handing the
2006 World Cup hosting duties to Germany over South Africa. His
actions disappointed Soccer New Zealand and the New Zealand
government.
</P>
<P>
On his return from the FIFA vote in Switzerland to Auckland,
the largest city in New Zealand, Dempsey said he would step down
as OFC president on October 1, but has now told Soccer New Zealand
his retirement will be effective immediately, according to Friday'
s evening program of Television New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The 79-year-old soccer stalwart handed his daughter and OFC
general secretary, Josephine King, a letter confirming his
retirement. He said his family had been under "tremendous pressure.
"
</P>
<P>
His sudden retirement means the OFC member nations have to vote
in a new head, which could take place as soon as Sunday next week
when it meets in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Bill MacGowan of Soccer New Zealand said there
have already been names put forward by those interested in the job
and the New Zealand soccer board will be meeting over the next few
days to decide who they will be backing for the position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
