<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Auto Sales Soar 43 Percent in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's automobile sales soared
43.1 percent year-on-year in the six months to June, driven by low
interest rates and an improving economic environment, local
industry figures showed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sales for the six months to June soared to 122,339 units, while
sales in June totaled 23,368 units, an increase of 17.4 percent
from the year before, said Toyota Motor Thailand, which prepares
the figures under an agreement between major car makers here.
</P>
<P>
The slower growth in June was due to price hikes, after a surge
in May, when car sales leapt 52.9 percent year-on-year to their
highest point for 31 months, it said..
</P>
<P>
"The adjustment of prices from time to time in the second
quarter by many auto companies resulted in the halting of sales,"
Toyota said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But it said that with the planned launch of several new models,
and strong sales promotions, a full-year target of 280,000 units
was expected to be reached.
</P>
<P>
A monthly average of 19,794 vehicles were sold in the first
half of this year, with nearly two-thirds of June's sales were
small pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
The three Japanese auto giants, Toyota, Isuzu and Honda,
dominated the Thai market with 62 percent market share in first-
half sales.
</P>
<P>
Car sales have boomed in Thailand as the economic recovery
gathers pace. Interest rates which soared into double digits
during the
financial crisis from mid-1997 now lie between 4 and 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Car sales are a key indicator of economic health and are
watched by analysts tracking Thailand's emergence from the 1997-
1998 recession.The government has forecast the economy will grow 5
percent this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
