<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theft of Signal Lights Puts River Traffic in Bangladesh at Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Navigation signal lights in the
country's three major rivers -- the Padma, the Jamuna and the
Meghna, are being stolen by an organized gang, putting the
movement of vessels in the waterways at serious risk.
</P>
<P>
Navigational signal lights, including buoys and beacons, worth
about 10 million U.S. dollars have been stolen during the last
five years, the Independent newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Due to the disappearance of Navigational signal lights, about
450 accidents on the 2,531 kilometers long vital river routes in
the country occurred during the period leaving over 120 people
dead and several hundreds injured and huge valuable goods damaged.
</P>
<P>
A high official of Bangladesh Inland Water Transport Authority
was quoted as saying that Traveling by launches, ferries and other
means of transport in the waterways has become very risky.
</P>
<P>
Besides, incidences of dacoity have also increased on the routs.
</P>
</TEXT>
