<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt to Strive for Economic Recovery: Senior Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
make tremendous efforts to push forward its economic recovery
program, a senior official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has made significant achievement in realizing its
economic recovery program, as the country recorded an increase in
its GDP (gross domestic product) by 3.21 percent in the first
three months of this year, Coordinating Minister for Economy,
Finance and Industry Kwik Kian Gie said in an exclusive interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"There are significant achievements we have made. Our GDP in
the first three months of this year increased by 3.21 percent,
investment up by 11.68 percent, exports increased by 9.07 percent
while imports rose by 3.97 percent," Kwik said.
</P>
<P>
"Inflation rate for January-May 2000 stood at 2.35 percent
while tourism (industry) increased by 4.05 percent during January-
April this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
But, Kwik added that the government will still have to get
around to some homework such as foreign debt restructuring and
combating rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
"And I think this is a key factor to make our currency of
rupiah regain strength. We also should reduce our foreign
borrowings step by step," Kwik said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has dropped sharply recently amid the rising
struggle among rival political parties in the country. It hit a 16-
month lowest level Wednesday with 9,500 rupiah to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The government set the exchange rate of rupiah within the
current fiscal year at the level of 7,000 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Some economic observers held that Indonesia is the only country
which has not been able to escape from the economic crisis as its
economic condition is still unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
They said apart from the political and security constraints,
other three main constraints are the very weak fundamental system
of national banks, the burdening bank recapitalization funds and
the very slow corporate debt restructuring.
</P>
<P>
"So, we should accelerate banking restructuring program and
privatization of state-owned companies," Kwik stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the collapse of the country's banking system has caused
the stagnant flow of fund for programs of the government and
private sectors and the suspension of monetary activities as well.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken 118 actions in connection with our economic
recovery program outlined in the letter of intent (LoI) signed by
the government and the International Monetary Fund. And now we are
in the process to continue our next programs with the Fund," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Indonesia's economic ties with China, the minister
said that Indonesia considered China as a major economic power in
the region.
</P>
<P>
"Well, I can say that China will be able to appear as an
economic major power in the region. China is also a potential
market for Indonesia," Kwik said, hoping that ties between the two
countries will be better and better in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0254 </DOCNO>
