<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Daohan Meets Visitors from Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Wang Daohan, the mainland's top
negotiator with Taiwan, has called for the resumption of talks
between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits on the condition that
the Taiwan side stops advocating "two states" theory and sticks to
the "one China" principle.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with a delegation from Taiwan's New Party here
Thursday, Wang, chairman of the Beijing-based Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), said that the
mainland has been sincere in resuming the talks between ARATS and
Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF).
</P>
<P>
If the SEF recognizes and accepts the consensus on the "one
China" principle reached between the ARATS and SEF in 1992, and if
the Taiwan side clearly commits itself to not advocating the "two
states" theory, the cross-Straits contacts and talks can be
resumed right away, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
However, some people in Taiwan distorted the consensus by
coming up with different interpretations of "one China," which has
actually placed barriers on the resumption of talks between the
two organizations.
</P>
<P>
Adherence to the "one China" principle is a responsibility and
obligation to both sides of the Taiwan Straits. It is the common
aspiration of the people on the mainland and Taiwan that the two
organizations, proceeding from the consensus, resume their talks,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Wang held a historic meeting with his Taiwanese counterpart Koo
Chen-fu, chairman of the SEF, in 1993, which led to a series of
technical negotiations. Talks were broken off in 1995 after the U.
S. visit by then Taiwan leader Lee Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with the delegation, Wang also expressed his
welcome to the group, while voicing his hope that the New Party
will play a bigger role in promoting cross-Straits exchanges and
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
