<HEADLINE> Remittance of S.Lankan Migrant Workers Reaches 300 Mln U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan migrant workers have
remitted a record 24 billion rupees (300 million U.S. dollars) in
foreign exchange from January to March this year, the official
Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Labor Minister John Seneviratne as saying that
a record 90 billion rupees (1.125 billion dollars) is expected
from migrant workers during the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said that this clearly indicated that the country's future
earnings in the foreign employment field will improve
significantly.
</P>
<P>
The migrant workers are important for this cash-starved Indian
Ocean island. Sri Lankan working abroad have topped the list of
foreign exchange earners in recent years, sending home 923 million
dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sri Lanka Bureau of Foreign Employment (SLBFE),
the total number of Sri Lankan workers abroad is estimated to be
around 788,000, of whom 65 percent are females mostly in the
Middle East countries as housemaids.
</P>
<P>
More recently Singapore, South Korea and Japan have also opened
their doors to Sri Lankan workers.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing the important role these migrant workers play in
the country's economy, the government has launched on several
welfare schemes for them and their families.
</P>
<P>
The SLBFE has negotiated special facilities for them such as
housing, bank loans, counseling and education facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
