<HEADLINE> Australia Threatens Fiji with Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard told Melbourne radio
station 3AW that "Mr. Chaudhry was illegally removed in a criminal
act and I think the behavior of the great Council of Chiefs in
bowing to (George) Speight's demands has been to betray the
democratic institutions of that country."
</P>
<P>
On the question of possible sanctions against Fiji, Howard
indicated that Australia was likely to take a stand, possibly on
an economic level and certainly on a personal one.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that "Severe sanctions hurt the people you
are trying to help," and "We are going to try and find the balance
in discussions over the next few days."
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Broadcasting Company, Australian
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said Friday before flying home
from Washington that Australia could impose sanctions against Fiji
as early as this weekend and any sanctions would depend on the
make-up of the new government in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
He would meet Prime Minister John Howard this weekend to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
"We absolutely would not accept George Speight in the
government or people who have been involved in hostage taking,
people who have been in the parliamentary compound, we've made
that very clear all along," he told the Radio.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Australian Associated Press reported that Fiji
coup leader George Speight stood up to confront the pressure
saying that there would be continued unrest if the nation was
returned to a constitutional, commonwealth style democracy.
</P>
<P>
He urged Australia and New Zealand to butt out of Fiji's
business and leave it to the native Fijians to direct the country'
s future.
</P>
<P>
"Any attempt by anybody to return Fiji to the status quo before
May 19 will be met with the same resistance we showed to the army
of this country," he told the Australian TV Channel Nine.
</P>
<P>
Heading an armed group, Speight took hostage on May 19 ethnic
Indian prime minister Mahendra Chaudhry and about 40 ministers as
well as parliament members of the country. Speight fanned up a
nation-wide unrest to force the military authorities to make a
compromise on Sunday and then the Great Council of Chiefs decided
Thursday to appoint former president Josefa Iloilo new president
of the country as Speight demands.
</P>
<P>
All hostages including Chaudhry were released Thursday. 
</P>
