<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME -- Chairman of the 36th Assembly of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) and Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema
Thursday called on African states to establish a peace-keeping
force to maintain peace in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Eyadema, who was elected OAU chairman early this week, told
Xinhua at his presidential residence that the idea of an African
peace-keeping force, which was first initiated by him at the 1994
OAU summit, has won wide support from African countries during the
just-closed summit here.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that though some African countries have defense
treaties with European countries, but once there is a turmoil in
the African continent, the Europeans are concerned only with the
safety of their soldiers. (OAU-Peace-keeping)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States and Vietnam on Thursday signed
a historic trade agreement, President Bill Clinton announced at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
"From the bitter past, we plant the seeds of a better future,"
said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He described the agreement as "another historic step in the
process of normalization, reconciliation, healing between our two
nations."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the agreement signed by U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky and Vietnamese Trade Minister Vu Khoan would
drastically open Vietnam's economy and increase trade between the
two countries. (US-Vietnam-Agreement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Visiting U.N. Mideast Envoy Terje Roed-Larsen said
here Thursday that the U.N. will step up its efforts to help
achieve a peace in the region under the framework of relevant U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a press conference after a meeting with
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah al-Khatib over the latest
developments in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The envoy stressed that the U.N. will mainly work under the
framework of all U.N. resolutions on the Middle East, and help
parties concerned to find solutions to their conflicts. (Jordan-
UN-Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The death toll has risen to 300 from Monday night's
oil pipeline explosion at villages near the oil town of Warri in
Nigeria's southern Niger Delta region, Information Minister Jerry
Gana confirmed in the capital of Abuja Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gana expressed the government's condolences to the families of
the victims and said that officials had been dispatched to the
scene for on-the-spot assessment. (Nigeria-Death Toll) 
