<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sacramento to Host U.S. Olympic Trials for Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Olympic trials for the
athletics will be kicked off on Friday in Sacramento, with the 100-
meter finals scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Greene, the world record holder and two-time world
champion in the 100 meters, is heavily favored to win the event in
the trials and the Sydney Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
However, he was admittedly nervous as his opponents feature
other sprinters including Michael Johnson, the Olympic double
champion in the 200m and 400m, and any failure to come home with a
gold medal would be devastating for the confident Greene.
</P>
<P>
"My career would be void ... it would be nothing if I don't get
an Olympic gold medal," said Greene, "It's the biggest meet of my
life. Nothing compares to this, not even the world championships.
"
</P>
<P>
"I'm getting very edgy, very anxious, trying to stay as calm as
possible," said the current top sprinter in the world.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago when Greene was 21, he failed to get through the
quarterfinals of the trials, finishing seventh in his heat, and
sat in the stands and cried uncontrollably during the Atlanta
Games.
</P>
<P>
"I told myself I would never let this happen again without me,"
said Greene, "I'm the world champion and the world-record holder,
but I need to get the gold medal to feel complete."
</P>
<P>
"I want to be the best sprinter ever, and if I don't get the
gold, I can't say I'm the best."
</P>
<P>
While Greene is the favorite for Olympic gold in the 100,
Johnson has that distinction in the 200m as he was the Olympic
champion and world record holder in the discipline.
</P>
<P>
However, the relationship between the two is frosty as Greene
has been bragging about how he is going to beat Johnson while
Johnson has called Greene "immature" and "disrespectful".
</P>
<P>
The two have met twice in the 200 wherein each won once, with
Johnson winning in 1997 and Greene in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic trials will run to July 23, as many an athletes are
seeking their glory moments in the coming Olympic Games, including
world heptathlon record holder Jackie Joyner-Kersee who is hoping
for her fifth consecutive Olympic outing in the long jump.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
