<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Couple Adopts Giant Panda on Web Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A couple from the United States
recently made the top bid in an Internet auction for a two-year-
old male giant panda which lives in the Wolong Nature Reserve,
southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The couple's bid of 6,100 U.S. dollars got them a giant panda
in the first Internet auction of the endangered species, according
to a local newspaper report.
</P>
<P>
In line with an agreement between the China Wildlife
Conservation Association and U.S. Internet company Twinbays
International, both individuals and enterprises from the U.S. are
eligible to participate in the annual bidding on the company's
website, twinbays.com.
</P>
<P>
All the bid money will be used in the research on giant pandas
by the Wolong Giant Panda Research Center.
</P>
<P>
The center will provide 40 giant pandas for bidding in the
first year. According to the agreement all the adopted giant
pandas will stay at the Wolong Nature Reserve.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. couple will stay updated on the progress of their new
giant panda, Mei Xiang, through written reports and e-mailed video
recordings.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 giant pandas have been adopted by people from the
U.S., Japan, Australia and other countries since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
There are only about 1,000 giant pandas, known as "living
fossils," in the world, all of them are in China, mainly in
Sichuan, Gansu, and Shaanxi provinces. About 100 of the pandas
live in Wolong Nature Reserve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
