<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pastrana Thanks U.S. Contribution to Plan Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Andres Pastrana
thanked Friday the United States' 1.3 billion dollar contribution
to the "Plan Colombia," aimed at development and the war against
drugs in the South American country.
</P>
<P>
"The international community has accepted, for the first time,
its share in the responsibility for the solution of the drug
trafficking problem," said Pastrana in a communique.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton signed Thursday the law that grants 1.3
billion dollars in special assistance to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), the biggest
guerrilla group in the country, said that Pastrana's Plan Colombia
is a threat for the country and for the peace process because it
is a counter-insurgent offensive disguised as a war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
The FARC said that the U.S. contribution contains a military
link between Washington and the Pastrana project.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. assistance includes the delivery to Colombia of 19 "
Blackhawk" and 42 "Huey" helicopters, as well as the training of a
second Colombian army battalion specialized in the fight against
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The United States' contribution had been requested at the end
of last year by the Pastrana government for the so-called "Plan
Colombia," a project against drugs and for the alternate
development and peace.
</P>
<P>
The program has a cost of 7.5 billion dollars, of which 4
billion dollars will be contributed by Colombia and 3.5 billion
dollars has been pledged by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Colombia obtained last week at a meeting of European donors a
total of 871 million dollars in assistance and credits pledges,
besides the U.S. assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Bridge To Invite Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The building of a second
bridge over the Panama Canal will be auctioned in November, said
Public Works Minister Moises Castillo on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The works would start at the beginning of next year and would
be concluded by March of 2004, said Castillo in statements quoted
Friday by the press.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet Council authorized the Public Works Ministry to
coordinate the call for the bidding with the Economy and Finance
Ministry, the General Comptrollership, and the Canal Authority.
</P>
<P>
The works are planned to have a total cost of 150 million U.S.
dollars, to be
financed by the Panama Canal Authority, said Castillo.
</P>
<P>
Several Asian firms, among them some from Japan, have shown
their interest in the construction of the bridge.  
</P>
