<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jury Awards $145 billion to Smokers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. jury in Miami ordered
the tobacco industry Friday to pay 145 billion dollars in punitive
damages to sick Florida smokers.
</P>
<P>
The six jurors, after a two-year trial of the case and hearing
157 witnesses, began deliberating the punitive damages question
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
They deliberated less than five hours before making the record-
shattering verdict that the cigarette companies had claimed would
amount to a "death warrant."
</P>
<P>
This is the first class-action lawsuit against the tobacco
industry by smokers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The smokers requested the tobacco companies to pay 196 billion
dollars as punishment for making a product that kills 430,000
Americans a year and for misleading the public.
</P>
<P>
Top executives from all five defendants, who made unusual
appearances at the court, argued that they didn't deserve to be
punished because they have changed their ways and are already
committed to paying billions of dollars to settle the lawsuits
brought by the states.
</P>
<P>
Philip Morris Inc.'s attorney, Dan Webb, called the trial
outcome "an unfair procedure, unheard-of in American history."
</P>
<P>
Any verdict in the case will be appealed and could take at
least two years to move through Florida's courts.
</P>
<P>
The defendants are Philip Morris Inc., Brown &AMP; Williamson, R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co., Lorillard Tobacco Co., Liggett Group Inc.
and the industry's Council for Tobacco Research and Tobacco
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The ruling was the largest jury damage award ever. The previous
record for punitive damages in a product-liability case was 4.8
billion dollars against General Motors last year in a California
car fire. A judge slashed the award to 1.09 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
