<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Volcano Copahue Spews Ashes Column </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Volcano Copahue is spewing a
column of ashes and water steam to a height of some 500 meters,
and the situation in the Chilean side is relatively calm despite
the explosions heard every 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
There is concern among the authorities of the Bio Bio province
for the Pehueche ethnic group community formed by three or four
families who live some 20 kilometers away from the Cophue because
the ashes are raining over their houses.
</P>
<P>
Northwestern winds carry the steam and the ashes over the
mountain range communities in the trans-Andean sector, so this
problem is being evaluated by the Argentine authorities, who plan
to move the inhabitants of the region in case the eruptions
activity increases.
</P>
<P>
Assessments made by Chilean experts determined that the Copahue
eruption will drop in intensity in the next hours. This volcano is
located in the limits between Chile and Argentina and its height
over sea level is 2,965 meters, and has seven craters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
