<HEADLINE> Britain Supports Kenya's Famine Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The British government has pledged
to provide 2 million pounds (about 3 million U.S. dollars) for the
emergency feeding operations in 19 drought-ravaged districts in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Acting British High Commissioner to Kenya Paul Harvey said here
Friday that the money was a united cash contribution which was
meant to support and boost the recent World Food Program (WFP)
appeal for 88 million dollars to the Kenyans under the famine, the
Daily Nation reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The latest contribution brings the British support to the
current drought relief activities to more than 5 million pounds (
about 7.5 million dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
WFP Country director for Kenya Arthur Holdbrook Friday said in
Nairobi that the U.S. government had pledged to donate 55,000 tons
of food to combat the famine in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Due to the prolonged drought, about 23 million Kenyans, 80
percent of the country's population, are facing the threat of
famine. Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi appealed to the
international community for emergency assistance to the Kenyans
early in June. 
