<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Lifts Duty on Egyptian Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya moved to diffuse a tariff
dispute with Egypt Friday after it agreed to remove suspended duty
on Egyptian rice, newspapers here reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister for Tourism, Trade and Industry Nicholas Biwott
Friday told the press that his government was committed to
adhering to COMESA (Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa)
tariff reductions and launching a free trade area by the end of
October this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the misunderstanding that led to the past allegations
by Egyptian Ambassador to Kenya Rifaat El-Ansary were due to
misinterpretation of Kenyan Gazette notice issued in November 1999,
which had imposed suspended duty on rice, wheat and wheat products.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Egyptian ambassador said that his
country would impose a 35 percent duty on Kenyan tea due to Kenya'
s suspended duty on Egyptian rice at the port of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
El-Ansary said here Friday that a big consignment of tea from
Kenya currently detained at Port Said would be released within the
COMESA protocol into Egyptian market.
</P>
<P>
El-Ansary said his country would only lift the 33 percent
tariff on Kenyan tea if the country (Kenya) takes a similar stand
on Cairo products.
</P>
<P>
Biwott reiterated that there was no trade war between the two
countries as it has been alleged, adding that Kenya and egypt
enjoy good bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He, however, regretted the "small" misunderstanding which was
brought about by a break down in communication, adding that the
matter has already been explained to the Egyptian Embassy.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Kenya, being COMESA member states, needed to adhere
to the regional tariffs as they are both beneficiaries of the
trade block, the ambassador said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
