<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FARC Welcomes U.S. Contribution to "Plan Colombia" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia (FARC) welcomed resources for 1.3 billion dollars
contributed by the United States to the "Plan Colombia" aimed at
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
This was stated Friday by Raul Reyes, a FARC spokesman in the
peace negotiations with the government of President Andres
Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome everything that comes for the development of the
country, said Reyes. "We do not oppose investment for social
development. The dollars that will arrive must solve such problems
as unemployment, lack of education and housing, and serve the
development of agriculture and livestock."
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader repeated the FARC opposition to the use of
part of the resources to give the armed forces helicopters and
planes to reinforce the war against drug trafficking "because it
should not be possible to be here talking for peace and at the
same time preparing for more war."
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the FARC, Colombia's largest rebel
group, expressed acceptance to the U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
Before this announcement, the FARC had said that Pastrana's
Plan Colombia is a threat for the country and for the peace
process because it is a counter-insurgent offensive disguised as a
war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. assistance includes the delivery to Colombia of 19 "
Blackhawk" and 42 "Huey" helicopters, as well as the training of a
second Colombian army battalion specialized in the fight against
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The United States' contribution had been requested at the end
of last year by the Pastrana government for the so-called "Plan
Colombia," a project against drugs and for the alternate
development and peace.
</P>
<P>
The program has a cost of 7.5 billion dollars, of which 4
billion dollars will be contributed by Colombia and 3.5 billion
dollars has been pledged by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Colombia obtained last week at a meeting of European donors a
total of 871 million dollars in assistance and credits pledges
besides the U.S. assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
