<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Not To Raise Tariffs for Entering Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Finance Minister Nicolas
Eyzaguirre said Friday that his country does not need to raise its
customs tariffs for its admission as a Southern Common Market (
Mercosur) full member.
</P>
<P>
The minister said at the State of Sao Paulo Industries
Federation (FIESP) installations that the next step is to agree on
a calendar for the tariffs of the other countries of the bloc to
be reduced to Chile's level, now 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Eyzaguirre said that Chile will have, when it becomes a full
member of Mercosur, a term in which it will continue with an
autonomy regarding customs tariffs and freedom to negotiate trade
agreements with other countries or blocs, while the other Mercosur
countries are in the process of adjusting their tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Since Brazil assumed the Mercosur presidency during the second
semester of this year, it has corresponded to President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso to consult with Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay
about the calendar of equalization of tariffs.
</P>
<P>
"If Cardoso has a favorable answer, we can present an advanced
report in Florianopolis by the end of the year," said the Chilean
minister, referring to the Mercosur summit scheduled for December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000714.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Not To Renounce Sovereignty Over Malvinas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Fernando
de la Rua said Friday that Argentina will not decline its claim of
sovereignty over the Malvinas Islands.
</P>
<P>
De la Rua explained that this does not mean hostility or will
affect the relations of his country with the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine president made this statement one day after the
Foreign Ministry presented a protest to the United Kingdom for "
violation of the Argentine air space."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry filed the protest Thursday night after
British aircraft overflew a fleet of Argentine fishing boats that
were operating within its exclusive economic zone and outside the
limits of the Outer Conservation Zone.
</P>
<P>
The British government rejected the Argentine protest, arguing
that "the British aircraft overfly that caused the Argentine
Foreign Ministry protest did not happen over Argentine waters,"
according to a communique issued Friday by the British embassy in
Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
British ambassador in Argentina William Marsden insisted when
he made these statements to the press in the French embassy in
this city that his country is not willing to negotiate the
sovereignty of the archipelago with the Argentine government.
</P>
<P>
However, Marsden considered that the incident in the Southern
Atlantic waters does not mean "a step backward" in the agreement
signed one year ago, and underscored that the relations between
both governments are "close and warm."
</P>
<P>
The two governments signed on July 14, 1999, an agreement that
reestablished the flights between the islands and the continent
and the access of Argentine citizens to the archipelago, which had
been suspended after the 1982 war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
