<HEADLINE> Jury Says U.S. Government Not Responsible for Waco Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal jury Friday
found that the government is not responsible for the death of 80
members of the Branch Davidian Sect in the 1993 siege of their
compound in Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
The five-member jury's verdict is only an advisory one, and U.S.
District Judge Walter Smithand will possibly make a final ruling
some time next month.
</P>
<P>
Jurors began deliberating Friday in Waco in the latest round of
a seven-year battle between Branch Davidians and the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
The plaintiffs charged that the government should be blamed for
the raid that started the 51-day armed standoff at the Davidian
compound and the final day of the siege, when the building went up
in flames after an FBI tank and tear gas assault.
</P>
<P>
The government argued that the federal agents were ambushed by
heavily armed Davidians in the raid and that suicidal members of
the group set the fires themselves on the final day.
</P>
<P>
"This was one of the most terrible and horrible events in our
history and they want to come into court and ask you to award them
a judgment," U.S. Attorney Michael Bradford, who defended for the
government, said in closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
But plaintiffs' lawyers called the deaths of the cult members "
the greatest domestic law enforcement tragedy in the history of
the United States."
</P>
<P>
The siege has sparked years of Congressional inquiries and
criminal trials. The U.S. Justice Department has appointed an
independent counsel to investigate how federal agents conducted
the operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
