<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean President, Mexican President-Elect Support L. American Front Creation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Ricardo Lagos
concurred with Mexican president-elect Vicene Fox in the idea of
creating a Latin American strategic front.
</P>
<P>
Lagos expressed his interest in the promotion of that alliance
in statements made during his visit to Brazil, the "La Tercera"
and "La Nacion" newspapers reported Friday
</P>
<P>
Fox described Chile, Brazil, and Argentina as "the ABC of South
America."
</P>
<P>
The winner of the July 2 Mexican presidential elections will
take office on December 1 as the first president who emerged from
the opposition of that country and whose voters ended 71 years of
the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) presidential hegemony.
</P>
<P>
Both newspaper underscored that Fox seeks a close relationship
with the Lagos government.
</P>
<P>
The first rapprochement of Fox with Chile dates back to 1997
during a forum in Santiago attended by the future Mexican
president when he was Guanajuato state governor.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Defense Vice Minister Gabriel Gaspar said that Fox has
a great interest in the Chilean experience, where ample coalitions
have been the dominant trend of the last three Chilean
administrations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
