<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Higher In Third Straight Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose in the
third straight session Friday after new data showed more signs of
the slowdown in the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 24.04 at 10,812.75.
The blue chip index rose 331.28 points in the six consecutive
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The technology
heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 71.32 at 4,246.18 and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 14.14 at 1,509.98.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose after three economic reports showed that the U.S.
economy was slowing and inflation remains under control in
response to six hikes in interest rates in the past year by the
Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported the Producer Price Index rose a
bigger-than-expected 0.6 percent in June because of the sharp rise
in energy costs. But the core rate of inflation at the wholesale
level, which excludes energy and food costs, fell an unexpected 0.
1 percent in the same month.
</P>
<P>
In another report, retail sales rose by a slightly bigger-than-
expected 0.5 percent, but sales rose just 0.2 percent, weaker than
expectations, when the volatile automobile category was excluded.
</P>
<P>
In a third report, industrial production at factories, mines
and utilities rose a 0.2 percent in June, the slowest pace since
last September.
</P>
<P>
The three reports raised hope that the Federal Reserve would
not raise rates again this year.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 4.09 at 664.80 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 2.95 at 942.38. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 0.13 at 542.63.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,593 up, 1,298 down and 487
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 947.15 shares from 1.02 billion in the
previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
