<HEADLINE> Former Kazakh Premier Released From Rome Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Former Kazakh Premier Akezhan
Kazhegeldin, arrested at Rome's main airport earlier this week on
the basis of an international warrant, was released Friday, the
Italian Justice Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry issued a statement saying that a Rome appeals
court Friday morning ordered the "immediate release" of
Kazhegeldin, a leading member of the Kazakh opposition who served
as premier in 1994-97.
</P>
<P>
It said that the court had "taken into consideration" Justice
Minister Piero Fassino's request that "the preventive detention be
lifted."
</P>
<P>
Kazhegeldin, 48, was arrested last Wednesday evening after
flying into Fiumicino airport from London and taken to Rome's
Regina Coeli prison on the River Tiber.
</P>
<P>
He is wanted in his home country on various corruption charges,
including money laundering and tax evasion, and is also accused of
"international terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Kazhegeldin and opposition parties insist that he is innocent
and that the charges against him are politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Justice Ministry had apparently been investigating
the possibility of complying with a request from Kazakh
authorities for his extradition although no extradition treaty
exists between Italy and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Kazhegeldin had lived abroad, in self-imposed exile, for the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
He was briefly arrested by the Russian authorities last year
after flying into Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
