<HEADLINE> Argentina, No.1 L. American Weapons Buyer: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Argentina spent in weapons
last year more than any other Latin American country, as reported
by the U.S. specialized magazine "Arms Trade News" in its most
recent edition.
</P>
<P>
The magazine reported that Argentina spent 223 million U.S.
dollars in the purchase of weapons in 1999, surpassing Brazil by
just 2 million dollars, while Chile was third with 177 million
dollars and Venezuela with 142 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report justified the Argentine expenditure in weapons,
explaining that it does not enforce a mandatory military service,
but a voluntary one, and for that reason it needs more equipment
for the professional military tasks.
</P>
<P>
Argentina bought last year 36 A4-AR fighter bomber planes,
modernized by the Lockheed Company in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that Latin America spent over 5 billion
dollars in ordnance during the last five years (1995-1999).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
